deck_excerpt: Swarm the Board with Level 1 Monsters to XYZ some big boys
deck_description:
Overarching Info

 

Vague Strategy:

For starters, the main strategy is to dump as many Lv.1's as possible on the board early to go into F0:Utopic Draco Future.

If you brick, then attempt to churn through the deck Magical Mallet or Card Destruction while leveraging the defensive cards to set up a board with more favorable conditions.

Sometimes though, you will get lucky and draw into some cards that facilitate the deck's gimmicks (Dystopia, Number 99: Utopic Dragon, Rank-up-Magic: The Seventh, AA-Zeus, etc.)

 

Most Notable Lv.1 monsters:

Jester Confit, Turbo Booster, and Big One Warrior are free (for the most part) special summons.

Kinka-byo is basically the only monster you want to normal summon if you have to.

Evil Thorn can be a great extender alongside Kinka-byo; and also a uniquely optimal One for One target. 

 

Treeborn Frog is Treeborn Frog; dump it in the GY with either foolish burial or Big One Warrior.

 

Boss Monsters:

'Dystopia the Despondent': A big beater, not that difficult to summon with the board swarm.

'Number 99: Utopic Dragon' + 'Number 99: Utopia Dragonar': Some signifigant beaters, only these one is reliant on any Rank-up-magic. First summon Utopia Roots then use a Rank-up-magic to bring out one of the Number 99's.

'F0: Utopic Draco Future': This is a retrain of the original F0 and is not reliant on a Rank-up-magic; this is brought out with the two Slacker Magician XYZs, next summon F0:Utopic Future, lastly bring out F0:Utopic Draco Future.

'Full Armored Crystalzero Lancer': This is more of a support piece for shutting down effect monsters as it is reliant on Rank-up-magic The Seventh; use that to summon Regular Number 101, then C101, the summon Full Armored Crystal Zero Lancer on top of C101.

'Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder': This guy is just mean. If you swarm the board, go into the Lyralusc XYZ, and then attack directly to satisfy the conditions to bring out AA-Zeus.

 

Categorizing the Main Deck:

 

Openers: 3x Big One Warrior, 3x Kinka-byo, 3x Evil Thorn, 3x Where Arf Thou?

 

Extenders: 3x Turbo Booster, 3x Jester Confit, 2x Jack in the Hand, 1x Instant Fusion, 1x Scapeghost, 1x Scapegoat, 1x One Day of Peace, 1x One for One, 1x Monster Reborn, 1x Card Destruction, 2x Magical Mallet, 1x Foolish Burial, 1x Treeborn Frog

 

Defensive Cards: 1x Ghostrick Dullahan, 3x Battle Fader, 1x Vijam, 1x Rainbow Kuriboh

 

Non-Engine Reqs: 2x Hyper Rank-up Magic: Utopiaforce

 

Mid/Late-game Bombs: 1x Rank-up Magic: The Seventh One, 1x Dystopia the Despondent

 

 

Categorizing the Extra Deck:

 

Instant Fusion Target: 1x Thousand-eyes Restrict

 

'Rank-up Magic: The Seventh One’ Targets: start with 1x No.101: Silent Honor Ark, into 1x No.C101: Silent Honor DARK, finishing with 1x Full Armored CRYSTALZERO Lancer

 

Rank 1 # XYZ + ‘Rank-up Magic’ Targets: start with 1x No. 39 Utopia Roots, finish with 1x No.99: Utopia Dragonar + 1x No.99: Utopic Dragon

 

Generic Rank 1 XYZ: Start with two of the following (1x Slacker Magician, 1x Ghostrick Dullahan, 1x Sylvan Princess), go into 1x F0: Utopic Future, finish with 1x F0: Utopic Draco Future

 

5 Materials on Field: start with 1x Assembled Nightingale, finish with 1x AA-Zeus

 

 

Notes:

I plan to eventually add in a 'combos' section

I will modify the deck/extra deck/side deck over time into a more refined form

Any suggestions, constructive or otherwise, are appreciated

 

Change log:

- 2x Rank-up-Magic: Argent Chaos Force, + 2x Hyper Rank-up-Magic: Utopiaforce

- 1x No.99: Utopic Dragon, + No.99: Utopia Dragonar

deck_excerpt: My personal deck to climb Masterduel Ladder for maximum rank - Spright Runick!
deck_description:
Second only to Ishizu Tearlaments, Spright Runick is arguably still the current reigning champion of Masterduel meta as of September 2023. 

Another great incentive to pilot this deck right now is that it is the strongest strategy that makes amazing use of I:P Masquerena! So if you pulled her recently released alternate art, then I highly recommend playing Spright Runick so you can watch her glorious animation again and again!
 
The ridiculously strong combination of Spright and Runick's smothering control and endless grind game create a deck that all strategies would have to fear and respect. Sprights ending on 3-5 interruptions (Sprind's bounce, Red's monster negate, Carrot's S/T negate, Smasher's banish, and I:P Masquerena's quick link) combined with Runick's draw 3 and multiple quick play spells generally stop any deck cold in their tracks. Both archetypes combined have a potential 10+ interruptions for your opponent to slog through, while maintaining a superior resource loop - outpacing most other strategies!
 
If you want to win and reach Masters 1 in Masterduel with a relentlessly strong resource-oriented control strategy, you've chosen to pilot the correct deck!

If you want a detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, check out my article from last month.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!


GLHF Duelists!
The main strategy revolves around Synchro summoning and banishing cards. The main Boss is Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying.

The main strategy revolves around flipping up and down your EARTH monsters.

The main bosses are Exxod, Master of The Guard and Subterror Behemoth Fiendess.

deck_excerpt: Theroycrafting a deck so I can play in a locals, but feel free to steal it if you like my ratios!
deck_description:
Do people hate you for playing Runick? Do they call you a "dirty stall player" for playing a deck that generates a lot of advantage while simultaneously trading one for ones with your opponent? Fear not! You can put a healthy dose of burn damage to the mix, so everyone on locals will despise you even more!
Introducing Runick Volcanics. This deck matches the unparalleled card advantage generation and spot removal of Runick, with the control aspect and newfound high burn capabilities of Volcanics to produce a deck that manages to outresource your opponent fast.

Being completely honest, I did not come up with this concept, but these are the ratios I ended up with. I am unsure if I like them or not, and I desperately wanted it to be 40 cards, but basically every Volcanics card is a three-of and 15 is the magic Runick number, so it is very hard to make space for it. You may cut Scattershot if you believe enough on the spot removal of Runick, since Scattershot sucks to draw. Sleipnir is also a possible cut, but I like her :)

Deck is entirely a 1 card combo so it can be crammed with a ton of non-engine and blind second. 1 card combo goes as follows: 

  1. Normal Reich-Heart
  2. Add Arrival
  3. Link Reich-Heart into Light-Heart
  4. Effect - add field spell. 
  5. Activate Field spell to add a Scareclaw or Visas. Whichever works. Any Scareclaw name is best, but Visas does come up as shown in my replays. 
  6. Special the card you added. 
  7. Activate Arrival and special back Reich-Heart. 
  8. Link all 3 into Tri-Heart. 
  9. Bob's your Uncle. You're free to activate Tri-Heart effect which revieves a Scareclaw and searches one then you're 75% of the way to lethal. 

This deck was a super easy climb. The hands it produces are gross. My twitch chat created the meme of "average scareclaw hand" because they look like 3-4 disruptions / board breakers & 1-2 starters more of the time. Of course, there are outliers. Every deck produces some bad hands, occasionally. Good luck if you decide to climb with this deck. It's super fun!

deck_excerpt: Fun combo deck that playes through a surprising amount of interaction, can be used on MD with no additions
deck_description:
This deck is relatively easy to learn the basics of but once you play it more you start to see its potential.

For MD i would replace triple tac with max c

going first I find its weaker thus the deck is more geared towards going second, though the deck can potentially put up an omni and a monster and spell negate under ideal circumstances.

going second it has good potential to OTK but you have to be quite careful with resource management or you could find yourself just off lethal. despite that it can usually play through a fair amount of interaction and set up some negates if you cant OTK.

Extra note about going second: if you think you can get to lethal without it dont use rookie fur hire as it locks you too only attacking with fur hire monsters, worst case senario use it to get too wiz or rafale through beat or something similar.

Extra note in general: the deck is usually pretty good at not bricking but usually you want two different fur hire monsters in hand (ideally 3)

good luck and have fun

deck_description:
<!-- [if gte mso 9]> <![endif]--><!-- [if gte mso 9]> Normal 0 21 false false false PT-BR X-NONE X-NONE <![endif]--><!-- [if gte mso 9]> <![endif]--><!-- [if gte mso 10]> /* Style Definitions */ table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-name:"Tabela normal"; mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0; mso-tstyle-colband-size:0; mso-style-noshow:yes; mso-style-priority:99; mso-style-parent:""; mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt; mso-para-margin-top:0cm; mso-para-margin-right:0cm; mso-para-margin-bottom:8.0pt; mso-para-margin-left:0cm; line-height:107%; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:11.0pt; font-family:"Calibri",sans-serif; mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"; mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi; mso-fareast-language:EN-US;}<![endif]-->

Objetivo do Deck é invocar o Obelisco, O Atormentador (tanto na mão como do cemitério), ou acabar com o Deck do Oponente impossibilitando de realizar uma compra.

O deck, funciona como um Mill Deck (Moinho) aonde se enviam as cartas de seu deck para o cemitério e por muitas vezes se enviam as do oponente (você não precisa se preocupar se ficar quase sem cartas, se no caso você tiver em seu controle (campo ou mão) a armadilha Troca de Espírito.

 

O deck também funciona desta forma para que Mudora ganhe um bônus de ataque de todos os monstros fada no cemitério.

Você também pode banir de seu cemitério um Energia da Alma MÁX e puxar um Obelisco, tanto de seu cemitério como de seu Deck para a mão. E caso você não tenha realizado invocações ainda neste turno, você pode usar a mágica Cruzar Almas usando os monstros do oponente como tributo necessário para trazer o Obelisco ao campo.  

Como Ishizu previa o futuro, tendo um monstro fada de terra na mão e Zolga , O Profeta. Você pode invocar o monstro fada de terra no campo, de forma normal e invocar especialmente o Zolga, O Profeta e desta forma ver as 5 primeiras cartas do seu deck e do deck do oponente. Caso você tenha ativo Armadilha do Coveiro, isto desencadeará um combo aonde o seu oponente não conseguirá comprar mais cartas do deck. E caso você tenha a Armadilha do Coveiro e não tenha nenhum Zolga em campo, você pode ativar a mágia Olho Senri  para realizar o mesmo feito.

 

Sempre dê preferencia de ter pelo menos uma Troca de Espírito na mão, e cuide para que o oponente não a venha descartar com o efeito de Arrastado para a Cova.

 

Use os efeitos de ¹Agido, o Sentina Antigo, ²Mudora, o Oráculo da Espada, ³Keldo, a Protetora Sagrada e ºKelbek, a Vangaurda Antiga no seu cemitério para recuperar as melhores cartas do Deck (neste caso não precisa priorizar o Obelisco, porque você tem outras formas de puxar ele)

Se Zolga, o Profeta for tributado para ser invocado pelo seu oponente para trazer um Lava Golem, ou O Dragão Alado de Rá -  Modo Esfera, ou um Kaiju; você pode usar o efeito de Zolga no cemitério destruir o monstro e causar 2000 de dano ao seu oponente.

deck_excerpt: A personal deck to help capture the feeling of playing an old school anime deck in the modern era of Yu-Gi-Oh!
deck_description: It's a bit of a hobby of mine to make, copy, edit, or otherwise think about character decks. Character decks which fit not only the original character's personality and playstyle, but also the vibe, be it the visual aesthetic of the cards, or how well their effects synergize. The typical philosophy is this; only run singles of each card unless you require multiple copies for a particular strategy, use as many cards that character actually used themselves (or a good substitute if the card doesn't exist in the actual game), maintain as much of the original vision, playstyle, and personality as possible, and beyond that just have fun. You're not limited in era so you can run as many retrains or modern support for the pre-existing cards as you want. But that's anime characters, this deck is my own personal character deck, which hopefully encapsulates me as much as possible, it's not meant to be competitive or even particularly good, just something I brainstormed one night while bored and winding down for bed.

This deck is my take on a competitive Tri Spright deck. The idea follows principles from older Tri-brigade formats in which a single card (usually Fraktall) can start a one card Spright Melffy combo all on its own, leaving plenty of room for extra disruption.

Combo 1: Frak sent from hand, dumping kitt then nerv. Player grabs Kerass then normal summons it. Player then specials bearbrum and uses its effect to grab Kitt from banished pile, summoning it to the field. Kerass and Bearbrum are overlayed to make Gigantic which summons Blue which brings Jet, grabbing Doublecross. These two overlay to make Melffy which gets Catty. Kitt's ability is then used to form Double Dragon Lord. Kitt and Melffy are linked to get Sprind, which dumps Angler, which brings two Beaver. The two Beaver are then linked into I:P. On opponent's turn Catty becomes Arch Light and I:P and Sprind can be used to make Gryphon or Apo.

This is the basic combo of the deck and should leave plenty of options to handle opponents' boards. Extra deck monsters fill the side deck to better navigate boards on the draw.

 

Hope everyone enjoys this weird mishmash. :)
Have fun!

deck_excerpt: Machines and burning... good pairing, apparently.
deck_description: As the name of the Deck suggests, this is my take on a modernized and non-archetypical character deck focused around the character Bandit Keith. Mainly this deck exists to burn, banish, or otherwise destroy and disrupt. Cards like Second Coin Toss were added to hopefully portray the sketchy nature of Keith and his tactics, borderline cheating to get the results he wants, while Jackpot 7 exists as the substitute for his 7 Completed Slot Machine play against Joey Wheeler. I didn't want this deck to be too strong, nor did I want it to just go full archetype. I tried to keep the spirit of Keith's original deck alive as much as possible while simply giving it a more modern take that - while definitely not something you wanna bring to a tournament - is at least a fun and usable Deck to use, or at least take notes from for a deck you yourself may be crafting involving a similar idea.

deck_excerpt: Limiter removal level max! All clear! C'mon, T.G. Glaive Blaster!
deck_description:
New T.G. support from AGOV goes so hard. No longer will I need to cope using Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights any longer.

The archetype is still fragile despite the new cards but less T.G. names comes with more engines to use at our disposal such as D/D Savant Kepler which enables us another way to make T.G. Mighty Striker. Diabellestar package is also here as well to bring out T.G. Rocket Salamander which itself is a 1-card combo without having to waste a normal summon. 

Again want to note that the archetype's combos are still fragile so running Crossout Designator may be necessary down the long run. I might also change the ratios on a couple of the T.G. monsters but they seem fine at the moment. Although I'm using some D/D/D cards, I really want to use D/D/D Vice King Requiem so badly because it's funny; however, the extra deck space is rather tight to add D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex for a slightly better end board that isn't "towers pass". Also Nibiru, the Primal Being is running rampant at the moment so might as well hold it off for now. All in all fun deck to mess around with and the combos aren't as rigid in contrast to when Crystron Halqifibrax was legal.

hand=Savant kepler.

hand=kepler + wonder xyz or trap trick.

ns kepler & activate it's effect to add gate. activate gate and use effect to add vice king requiem. place requiem in the pendulum zone, and activate its effect, sending gate to the gy, and ss itselt, don't change its lv. tribute kepler and requiem for gilgamesh. activate gilgamesh to place savant thomas and orthros in the pendulum zones. activate thomas's effect to add kepler back to hand. use gilgamesh's gained effect(from requiem) to shuffle gate from the gy to the deck and pop thomas. activate kepler into the pendulum zone. pendulum summon thomas and requiem in the zones gilgamesh points to. set wonder xyz/trap trick.use thomas, pop kepler and ss ragnarok from deck. end your turn. in your opponents draw phase, activate wonder xyz/traptrick. if its trap trick, then set wonder xyz, and activate it on the resolution. use wonder xyz, xyz summon kali yuga w/ rangnarok and thomas., locking your opponent out of all card effects. in the end phase of your opponents turn. use kali yuga to destroy all spells/traps on the field. on your turn you can make machinex with your gilgamesh. and this should be enough to attack for game, or combo some more, and then attack for game.

deck_excerpt: Clockwork Night and Duality are incredible tools for Cyber Dragon in Masterduel!
deck_description:
Cyber Dragon has long been a pet deck of mine since forever - I mean, who doesn't like giant serpentine killer robot dragons?! That's such a cool concept for a Yugioh deck! Ever since I've watched GX in my childhood, the machine archetypes of that Yugioh generation have captured my heart - including the Cyber Dragons. However, this archetype has (so far) never reached competitive viability and has always been a mediocre rogue deck.

This changes with the introduction of Masterduel's relatively new secret pack Inherited Unity! This set includes two new cards that are integral and powerful to the Cyber Dragon arsenal - Clockwork Night and Duality!
 
Playing directly with Cyber Dragon's gimmick of contact fusing with opponent's machine monsters, Clockwork Night's fieldwide machine transformation effect suddenly turns Chimeratech Fortress Dragon into a "kaiju" for your opponent's entire board! Clockwork Night's attack boost helps immensely as well, simultaneously boosting all your machine monster's ATK while lowering your opponent's.
 
Duality allows much easier access to Chimeratech Rampage Dragon, furthering your plays with it's double foolish burial and up to whopping 6300ATK points of damage! It can also turn your Fortress and Megafleet Dragon into Cyber Twin Dragon and Cyber End Dragon! 
 
While Cyber Dragon is functionally the same, these two cards further enhance the strategy's ability to break through boards and do what Cyber Dragons do best, OTK with ridiculously high levels of ATK!
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 
This Cyber Dragon deck is played "pure" without any supporting engines. 3 Herz, 3 Core and 3 original Cyber Dragon as well as Cyber Emergency are played, giving the duelist consistent access to a Cyber Dragon name. Along with Clockwork Night, Any one of these monsters contact fuse the opponent's entire board. Triple Herz and Core are played as well, so that they can benefit from Machine Duplication. 1 Cyber Revsystem is included as an additional search target for Core and for extra extension. 
 
1 Regulus is played as an Earth Machine search target for Clockwork Night. Regulus also combos very well with Herz, since it can trigger it's "sent from field to GY" effect. 
 
1 Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju is played as a board breaking search target for Cyber Repair Plant. It's high 3300ATK shouldn't matter, since it can be contact fused away into Fortress Dragon because it's a machine. 
 
9 handtraps are played as well as the "Maxx C" package of Crossout and Called By the Grave to slow down your opponent and to help enable OTKs happen more easily. 
 
The Extra Deck is designed to compliment Duality's ability to turn monster on the field into their Light/Dark counterpart. Cyber Dragon -> Rampage Dragon, Fortress Dragon -> Cyber Twin Dragon, Megafleet Dragon -> Cyber End Dragon. Duality can also dodge any sort of targeting interruption your opponent has!
 
The deck is 40 cards so that it is as consistent as possible to help facilitate what it's designed to do - OTK going second. 

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN

 

Blind Second Cyber Dragon has one strategy - go second, obliterate an opponent's board and OTK! Here are some classic Cyber Dragon combos: 

 

Cyber Dragon Core + Galaxy Soldier = 9500ATK, Omni-negate, destroy up to two spells/traps. 
  1. Normal summon Cyber Dragon Core. Activate Core's effect to search for Cyber Emergency. 
  2. Activate Cyber Emergency to search for Cyber Dragon Herz. 
  3. Link away Core for Almiraj. Link away Almiraj for Secure Gardna. (Alternatively, if you have Clockwork Night, contact fuse your opponent's board away)!
  4. Activate Galaxy Soldier's effect to summon itself, sending Herz. 
  5. CL1 Herz to search for Cyber Dragon, CL2 Galaxy Soldier to search for another Galaxy Soldier. 
  6. Activate Galaxy Soldier's effect to summon itself, sending Cyber Dragon. 
  7. XYZ summon Cyber Dragon Nova using Galaxy Soldier + Galaxy Soldier. 
  8. Activate Nova's effect to summon Cyber Dragon from GY. 
  9. Overlay Cyber Dragon Infinity on top of Nova. If opponent still has a monster on-field, activate Infinity's effect to attach their monster as material. 
  10. Link summon Predaplant Anaconda using Cyber Dragon + Secure Gardna. 
  11. Activate Anaconda's effect, copying Overload Fusion's effect. Fusion summon Chimeratech Rampage Dragon, banishing from GY Cyber Dragon and Herz as material. 
  12. On summon, Rampage Dragon destroy up to two spells/traps on your opponent's field.
  13. Activate Rampage Dragon's effect to send to GY two light machines to GY so it can attack 3 times. 
  14. Enter battle phase, and you have a total of 9500ATK on board to OTK with (Rampage -  6300ATK, Infinity - 2700ATK, Anaconda - 500ATK). 

 This same combo can be done if you have Cyber Dragon Core + Herz. Instead of searching Cyber Emergency with Core, search Cyber Repair Plant. Link away Core so that it goes into the GY, and Cyber Repair Plant searches for Galaxy Soldier! 

 

Cyber Dragon Core/Herz + Machine Duplication = 9500ATK, Omni-negate, destroy up to two spells/traps. 

 

  1. Normal summon Cyber Dragon Core/Herz. if you summoned Core, search for your "Cyber" spell of choice. (Emergency for another search, Repair Plant to search for Kaiju, Revsystem for extension).
  2. Activate Machine Duplication targeting Core/Herz, summoning 2 Cyber Dragon from deck. 
  3. Link away Core for Almiraj. Link away Almiraj for Secure Gardna. (Alternatively, if you have Clockwork Night, contact fuse your opponent's board away)!
  4. XYZ summon Cyber Dragon Nova using Cyber Dragon + Cyber Dragon. 
  5. Repeat steps 9 -> 14 detailed above. 

 

This is another variant of the combo with the same end result, but with Machine Duplication. 

 

GENERAL TIPS

  • Clear the board first, then go for full Cyber Dragon combo to OTK! It's very difficult to OTK if you're interrupted at any point. 
  • If your opponent targets your Cyber Dragons for any effect, you can dodge them using Duality while summoning a powerful monster from Extra Deck!
  • Clockwork Night is excellent bait for your opponent to negate. If they don't remove it from the field and you have a Cyber Dragon on board, their whole field will be contact fused away!
  • Many handtraps are included in this deck to simplify your opponent's boardstate making them easier to OTK. Be sure to time your handtraps properly to weaken your opponent!
  • If your opponent Maxx C's you while you're trying to combo, just keep going and go all-in on OTK! All the cards won't matter if their lifepoints are 0.
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

 

Cyber Dragon, one of the coolest machine decks ever has got a great boost with Duality and Clockwork Night! Contact fusing your opponent's entire board feels incredibly good and satisfying while generating advantage and firepower with Duality streamlines Cyber Dragon into another level!
 
While Cyber Dragon isn't competitively viable (it's only rogue for now), if piloted correctly it can win consistently vs. top decks on Masterduel Ladder.
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_description:
A Deck created by ChatGPT using the prompt "Create a Elemental HERO Deck with a short description of how the deck is played in Yu-Gi-Oh!"

 

Please bear in mind that as useful ChatGPT is, it is by far not perfect. There will be inconsistencies and problems with deck building. Most of the time it will create a deck either under 40 cards or randomly have extra deck cards in the main deck. I've done some fine tuning whilst trying to not impact too much what ChatGPT has made.

 

A short description made by ChatGPT about how the deck functions.

The Elemental HERO deck is centered around summoning powerful HERO monsters and using their fusion abilities to control the field and apply pressure to your opponent. Here's how this deck works:

Elemental HERO Neos: This is the core HERO monster. You can use cards like "E - Emergency Call" and "A Hero Lives" to quickly get Neos on the field. Neos Alius is another strong option to summon, and it can be used as fusion material.

Fusion Summons: Use "Polymerization" and "Miracle Fusion" to fusion summon your Elemental HERO fusion monsters. "Elemental HERO Absolute Zero" and "Elemental HERO The Shining" are powerful fusion monsters that can help you control the field and recycle your banished HERO monsters.

Masked HEROes: "Mask Change" allows you to transform your HERO monsters into Masked HEROes during the Battle Phase. "Masked HERO Dark Law" is a particularly potent choice as it can disrupt your opponent's graveyard and hand.

Search and Support: "Elemental HERO Blazeman" helps search for Polymerization and can send a HERO from your deck to the graveyard, setting up for Miracle Fusion. "Elemental HERO Shadow Mist" searches for Mask Change and other HERO cards. "Elemental HERO Solid Soldier" is a useful Normal Summon that can special summon another HERO from your hand.

Draw and Consistency: Cards like "Reinforcement of the Army" and "E - Emergency Call" help you search for your HERO monsters quickly. "Elemental HERO Bubbleman" can be special summoned if you have no other cards in hand, which can lead to an easy Xyz summon.

Protection and Removal: "Elemental HERO Honest Neos" provides battle protection for your HERO monsters. "Dark Bribe" can be used to negate your opponent's key spells and traps. "Solemn Judgment" helps protect your plays.

Extra Deck: The Extra Deck includes various HERO fusion monsters and Masked HEROes to cover different situations. "Elemental HERO Neos Knight" is a formidable attacker, while "Masked HERO Acid" can wipe out your opponent's backrow. "Xtra HERO Cross Crusader" can recycle your banished HERO monsters.

This Elemental HERO deck is versatile and can adapt to different situations, making it a fun and competitive choice for HERO enthusiasts.

deck_description:
A Deck created by ChatGPT using the prompt "Create an Invoker Deck with a short description of how the deck is played in Yu-Gi-Oh!"

Please bear in mind that as useful ChatGPT is, it is by far not perfect. There will be inconsistencies and problems with deck building. Most of the time it will create a deck either under 40 cards or randomly have extra deck cards in the main deck. I've done some fine tuning whilst trying to not impact too much what ChatGPT has made.

A short description made by ChatGPT about how the deck functions.

The Invoked archetype focuses on Fusion Summoning powerful monsters by using "Aleister the Invoker" and various Fusion Spells. Here's how this deck works:

Aleister the Invoker: Aleister is your key card. He's used to Fusion Summon your Invoked monsters. "Aleister the Invoker of Madness" is another version of Aleister that can be special summoned from your hand, and he gains attack points for each Fusion Spell in your GY.

Fusion Spells: "Invocation" is the primary Fusion Spell for Invoked monsters. It allows you to use monsters from your hand or field as Fusion Materials, and it recycles itself when it's in the GY. "The Book of the Law" is another Fusion Spell that can be used to perform Fusion Summons during your Battle Phase, catching your opponent off guard. "El Shaddoll Fusion" and "Instant Fusion" give you access to additional Fusion monsters, such as "El Shaddoll Winda" and "Thousand-Eyes Restrict."

Hand Traps: Cards like "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring," "Effect Veiler," and "Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion" help you disrupt your opponent's plays and protect yourself.

Protection and Negation: "Magical Meltdown" and "Terraforming" protect your Fusion Spells from being negated by your opponent's card effects. "Invocation" and "The Book of the Law" have built-in protection against card effects that would negate them. "Aleister the Invoker of Madness" can be used to negate and banish a monster your opponent controls.

Draw Power: "Maxx "C"" allows you to draw cards when your opponent Special Summons. It can discourage your opponent from overextending.

Disruption and Control: "Infinite Impermanence" and "Solemn Strike" are your disruption and control cards, allowing you to negate your opponent's monster effects and special summons.

Extra Deck: Your Extra Deck consists of Invoked Fusion monsters, as well as some utility monsters like "Thousand-Eyes Restrict" and "Millennium-Eyes Restrict" for monster control. "Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians" is useful for Link plays.

This Invoked deck provides a balance of Fusion Summoning power, disruption, and control, making it a versatile and competitive choice for both casual and competitive play.

A short description made by ChatGPT about how the deck functions.

The Plunder Patroll archetype focuses on controlling the field and stealing your opponent's monsters. Here's how this deck works:

Main Monsters: The core Plunder Patroll monsters - Redbeard, Whitebeard, Goldenhair, Bluebeard, Silverd, and Blackbeard - serve as your primary monsters. They have effects that allow you to equip them to your opponent's monsters, taking control of them and gaining their effects.

Support Monsters: Hand traps like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Effect Veiler help with disruption and defense..

Spell Cards: Plunder Patroll Shipshape Ships Shipping, Plunder Patroll Booty, and Plunder Patroll Shipyarrrd are essential for the archetype. They help you control the field, search for your Plunder Patroll monsters, and trigger their effects. Terraforming and Reinforcement of the Army ensure you have access to these key spells.

Fusion Summons: Instant Fusion allows you to quickly bring out Thousand-Eyes Restrict or other Level 1 Fusion Monsters for Link plays or to steal opponent's monsters.

Traps: Plunder Patrollship Lys is a powerful trap card that can help you control the field further and provide protection.

Extra Deck: The Extra Deck contains various Plunder Patroll fusion monsters, each with unique abilities. Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy and Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon are included for their powerful effects. The other Extra Deck monsters provide utility and removal options.

The strategy of this deck is to disrupt your opponent with hand traps, control the field with your Plunder Patroll monsters, and use fusion summons and Link plays to apply pressure and maintain board control.

The goal here is to set up DNA Surgery and Insect Barrier as soon as possible to lock out the opponent's attacks. Use your monsters for offense and to defend your combo, and always keep an eye out for potential threats to the DNA Surgery/Insect Barrier lock. The rest of the deck provides versatile options for different situations.
Another goofy deck with probably no function. I looked at each of these archetypes and I wanted to try and combine all of them. :)

There is a lot to go over, so I'll try to keep it concise.

First to note is the Amazoness lineup - Paladin, Swordswoman, and Tiger. These are pretty much the only ones you need. Chain Master is a solid choice too, but for this deck specifically we aren't going to consider her. Besides them, we have 3x Giant Rat and 2x Marauding Captain to help swarm. D.D. Assailant rounds out the warrior lineup - the rest of the monsters are generic staples.

The spell and trap lineup is very standard - the only cards I want to note are Amazoness Archers and Ojama Trio. These go hand-in-hand to force your opponent to attack and deal some serious damage.

The side deck is a little unusual but I think it's pretty solid. Spell Canceller helps against Reasoning Gate. Tribe helps against any deck that runs a... well, tribe. Mind Control is for Chaos. Book of Moon and Lightning Vortex are both present for countering goat control, but Book in general is just insanely good. Cylinder and the two Pikeru counter burn, and Saku counters warriors/aggro.

One final note - if the main deck cost is too steep swap out Delinquent Duo for Lightning Vortex - that'll cut about $30.

Love this archetype, always played with it. This is a version that I ended up playing in ranked Master Duel. Not a Meta deck, but a fun one to play with. Main objective is to have a Daigusto Sphreez and a Gusto Gulldo on your field and a big monster on your opponent side of the field, than splash your monsters on the opponent's monsters.

Gusto Griffin is a great engine to special summon new monsters. Cards like Wynn the Wind Channeler, One for One, Forbidden Chalice and Tailwind of Gusto (on the grave) make  this engine work. Sometimes i like to summon Gusto Vedir to send Gusto Griffin to the grave, than find a way to summon Daigusto Sphreez to bring back Gusto Griffin to the hand so I can discard it with another card.

Windwitches have some great synergies with gusto. You always want to start with a Windwitch - Ice Bell in hand. With only one card you can summon Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon. You want Wind Pegasus @Ignister as a material, so when a monster you control is destroyed, you can activate its effect on the graveyard. Pilica, Descendant of Gusto is amazing with these cards, after summoning a crystal wing, you can summon pilica to special summon Windwitch - Glass Bell and make another synchro monster.

The goal of this deck it to use the low level Witchcrafter monsters to summon the high level Witchcrafter monsters; primarily Witchcrafter Madame Verre (to access monster negates) and -Witchcrafter Haine (to access face-up targeting destruction + Spellcaster protection), by pitching the in-archetype Spell cards (that come back to your field/hand during your End Phase). With my personal tech choices, this deck's power increases exponentially, allowing you to make it known to your opponent that even Rogue decks can be meta!

deck_excerpt: Put your x3 Spellbook structure deck to competitive use!
deck_description:
Ever since Dogmatika debuted came out about three years ago, I've greatly admired the archetype. The Christian theming, Dark Souls-like artwork and the Extra Deck dumping playstyle is just too perfect! With the recent unlimit of the deck's ace card, Nadir Servant with the latest banlist and the recent support released into Masterduel, I'd say it's time to unleash the power of the corrupt clergy on ladder!
 
This version of Dogmatika is augmented by Spellbook cards, providing for insane advantage while summoning Jowgen during the endphase! After resolving Spellbook of Judgment and Alba Zoa's effect, you effectively FTK your opponent as most of their extra deck is in the GY and Jowgen prevents any special summoning! Your follow-up for next turn is often a 5-7 card hand full of Spellbooks and Dogmatika cards, since Spellbook of Judgment + Dogmatika gather incredible amounts of resources every turn.
 
Being a "rogue" and relatively unknown deck, Spellbook Dogmatika isn't to be underestimated - it can fight toe to toe with the strongest decks on Masterduel! Put your x3 Spellbook structure deck to competitive use!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
The SPELLBOOK portion of this deck is composed of 14 cards. It is designed to max out on ways to get Spellbook of Judgment, since it represents a large portion of this deck's power with the Jowgen lock and potentially giving you up to 6 cards at the end phase. 3 Spellbook of Eternity, 3 Spell Magician of Prophecy and 2 Judgment give you 8 copies of this key card. The other Spellbook cards are a "toolbox" that you can choose from whether you want a draw 2 (Spellbook of Knowledge), interruption (Spellbook of Fate), or monster reborn (Spellbook of Life). 
 
The DOGMATIKA cards form the other half of the deck, composed of 18 cards. This deck core is designed to turbo out the Dogmatika ritual boss monsters as fast as possible, and to initiate the Extra Deck milling strategy so you can begin gaining resources while methodically destroying your opponent's Extra Deck. The majority of the Extra deck are milling targets for your various Dogmatika cards - each part of a toolbox with various effects (N'tss destroys, Arc Light searches rituals, Garura draws 1, etc). 
 
A tiny BRANDED package is composed of 2 cards - Branded Fusion and Fallen of Albaz. Branded Fusion is searchable by dumping to the GY Albion - so it can help push for OTK your following turn. Also, if you draw into Branded Fusion you can bring out Mirrorjade, an Extra Deck monster so you can start special summoning your Dogmatika monsters. 
 
As usual, the essential MAXX C package (3 Ash, 3 Maxx C, 2 Called By and 1 Crossout) is included in this deck so that you have as much possible chance to win the "maxx c" minigame. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The idea with mixing Spellbooks with Dogmatika is to activate Judgment first, then activate as many spell cards as possible to maximize the rewards you get from Spellbook of Judgment. After you finish the Spellbook portion of your strategy, the Dogmatika cards use many spells to search and ritual summon as well. Ideally, if you are allowed to fully combo, you should have sent a majority of your opponent's Extra Deck to the GY with your various Dogmatika cards (Alba Zoa, Matrix, Maximus), locked them from special summoning (Jowgen) and received about +6 drawing multiple times (Spellbook of Knowledge/Garura) and searching with Judgment! Even if your opponent manages to break through your field, you will definitely have enough follow-up next turn to OTK since Dogmatika monsters (usually with Albaz Zoa and White Relic). 
 
Dogmatika's new win condition is summoning their ridiculously powerful boss monster Alba Zoa as soon as possible. Not only does it render Dogmatika monsters on the field unaffected by Extra Deck Monster effects, it forces your opponent to either send their Extra Deck/Hand to the GY or return every Extra Deck monster they have on their field! This easy to summon card makes OTKs extremely easy (it has 4000ATK!), makes your more resillient, and renders Extra Deck centered strategies void. 
 
After you control your opponent, lock them out and destroy all their resources, the Dogmatika cards should generate enough beatsticks to allow you to push for game next turn. Spellbook Dogmatika is basically a spell heavy version of a similar strategy, Floowandereeze. Summon floodgates and beatsticks to lockdown and control your opponent to victory - only this time you spam spells like a Runick/Sky Striker player. 
 
Depending on what you draw, the combos of this deck varies. Sometimes you only get either archetype of the deck and not the other. Most hands get both Spellbook and Dogmatika on board. Both strategies are competent on their own, but ideally both Spellbook and Dogmatika prefer to be up and active. 
 
Spellbook Magician of Prophecy + Nadir Servant = Jowgen's Special Summon Lock, +3 to +8 cards in hand (various searches, draw effects + Judgment), most of your opponent's Extra Deck milled (Dogmatika card effects), 4000ATK/DEF Dogmatika beatstick (Alba Zoa) on field. 
  1. Normal summon Spellbook Magician of Prophecy. Search Spellbook of Judgment. 
  2. Activate Spellbook of Judgment. This will summon Jowgen in the endphase, and search you Spellbook cards up to the number of spells you activated.
  3. Link summon Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden using Magician of Prophecy. 
  4. Activate Nadir Servant, sending Garura. Search for Ecclessia. Draw 1 card with Garura's effect.
  5. Special summon Ecclessia now that there is an Extra Deck monster on the field. Search for Maximus.
  6. Special summon Maximus by banishing Garura in the GY. 
  7. Activate Maximus' effect to send two to the GY from your Extra Deck and your Opponent's Extra Deck. Send Arc Light + another ED monster of your choice.
  8. Arc Light searches for any Ritual monster/spell. Search for the missing pieces to summon Alba Zoa depending on the cards in your hand. Ideally, you should get Dogmatikalamity and Alba Zoa.
  9. Activate Dogmatikalamity to summon Alba Zoa. 
  10. Activate Alba Zoa's effect to mill half of your opponent's Extra Deck. 
  11. During the End Phase, the effect of Spellbook of Judgment resolves, summoning Jowgen from deck, and adding up to 6 different Spellbook Spells to your hand. Also, if you sent Albion or Titaniklad to the GY, search for Branded Fusion and your Dogmatika monster of choice!
With two cards the deck's endboard is a special summon lock with Jowgen, several Dogmatika beatsticks, a fatty hand of 6+ cards, and enough follow-up next turn for you to easily OTK. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Before using your draw effects like Garura and Spellbook of Knowledge, try to thin out your deck first by finishing your searches first. This increases the chances of you drawing an important starter or a unsearcheable staple like Ash Blossom!
  • A great card to use in this deck is Secret Village of Spellcasters. This spellcaster centered floodgate card generally is an auto-win (vs. decks like Branded for example), especially when you face decks that heavily use spellcards but don't have any spellcasters. 
  • Droll & Lockbird absolutely destroys this deck. If your opponent resolves this card vs. you, it essentially skips your turn. Good thing Droll isn't used much in Masterduel! 
  • White Relic is an OTK card, best used in turn 3. In turn 3 when its your turn to conduct an attack, you can ritual summon White Relic and use its effect targeting itself and Alba Zoa. Her attack will reach 4500, allowing you to push for an easy OTK!
  • Remember that this deck is a spell heavy version of a similar strategy, Floowandereeze. You turbo out floodgates, get a ton of resources and OTK with beatsticks - the only difference is that you spam spells instead of normal summons! 
  • Buy the x3 Spellbook Structure deck for the spellbook cards to save on your UR and SR points!
 Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Ever wanted to be the villain duelist in Yugioh who summoned eldritch abominations from beyond, while fiendishly locking your opponent from playing the game? Well Spellbook Dogmatika is the perfect deck for you! Laugh like a madman as you mill most of your opponent's Extra Deck, while locking them out of special summoning with Jowgen! In 2023, this ancient 10 year olf strategy stands strong since it is augmented with Dogmatika - rendering the strategy able to compete with the big league decks on Masterduel ladder!
 
 GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Trying out the new Silenforce ritual archetype
deck_description:
During testing I've found that the deck is focused around 4 things.

You want Novox, Skull Guardian, non-ritual Sauravis, and Silenforcing Barrier on the field by the end of your turn.

Novox will get you Barrier which will in-turn protect all your LIGHT monsters.

Skull Guardian acts as an omni-negate and 4100 beater when Novox is on the field. The relationship between Skull Guardian and Novox is similar to Rescue-ACE Hydrant and Turbulence. You kinda want them both on the field, but the Level 1 is more important if you can only have one.

Non-ritual Sauravis can go into any of your ritual monsters except Benten. You can go into Ritual Sauravis to return to hand and negate and banish a special summon, which sets up a hand-trap negate in case Barrier gets removed.

If non-ritual Sauravis' effect counts as a ritual summon, you can also go into Pendulumgraph to burn your opponent, negate a spell, summon an Odd-Eyes from the Extra Deck, then search a ritual spell during the End Phase.

Ritual Saffira is good going first, due to its hand ripping effect in the end phase. It's also useful if you need to return Novox from GY to hand, or to get more cards in hand.

Ideally, you want Novox and Silenforcing Barrier out as soon as possible. This can be expedited using Diviner, Benten, and One for One.

Diviner, sending Herald of the Arc Light, then ritual summoning using Diviner will allow you to special summon Novox from deck.

Tributing Benten for a ritual summon will add Novox to hand.

One for One will also special Novox. This is why I've chosen Effect Veiler over Infinite Impermanence. Veiler plus a Level 6 Diviner can also give you the levels for your Level 7 Rituals.

Pre-Preparation is good because Skull Guardian, Sauravis, and Saffira are all mentioned on the ritual spell.

Preparation is good because it can search all your ritual monsters. It's also easy to get the ritual spell in grave to retrieve using Preparation.

The trap Authority offers an alternative target for Novox's effect and acts as an additional searcher if you happened to open Barrier.

The extra deck is pretty free outside of the Diviner targets. I added some targets for Pendulumgraph, as well as some Rank 7s since most of the cards you'll be summoning are Level 7s. I tried to pick out some good LIGHTs since they'll be protected by Barrier. I added some generic Links that work with LIGHTs and Rituals. Feel free to change it up as needed.

Overall, the ratios felt good, but I'm always open to some constructive criticism.

I was sitting through my biology lecture and got bored to the point where I realized how I never tried building Lady of Lament with Armored Xyz when Full Armored Xyz is a Normal Trap. The whole Armored Xyz line is simple. It all starts with 2 Level 3's going into Xyz Armor Torpedo, detaching 2 to draw 1, overlaying into Xyz Armor Fortress, and detaching to add Full Armored Xyz. It's a cool thing to do when your Deck is running enough Level 3 or 4 monsters to go into a Rank 3 or 4. And this brings us here to Lady of Lament Full Armored Xyz. You have the option of doing your usual Lady of Lament shenanigans or going through the whole Armored Xyz line with Tour Guide From the Underworld and ending on the ability to go into a Full Armored DARK Lancer with its attach effect live while also backing it up with a bunch of Traps. Or, you can just do both: go through the whole Armored Xyz line for DARK Lancer access while also having Lilith setting you Traps. In addition to that, you also have the option of using the Armored Xyz cards as an OTK tool on turn 3 after you've gotten through your opponent's turn with your Traps. To accomplish this, we are playing some Burning Abyss monsters in order to help get out a Rank 3 and/or to help get a Level 3 DARK Fiend on the field without relying on your Normal Summon.

For monsters: 3 Lord of the Heavenly Prison. This is our only big Main Deck monster we are playing. I find that Doomdog Octhros and Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle to be much more of a hindrance in this Deck since we want to have Tour Guide get out BA's and have BA's in hand instead. Lord gives protection to your set backrow and it can get you a Spell/Trap from Deck which is much more useful. 3 Lilith, Lady of Lament and 3 Alice, Lady of Lament. Lilith Tributes a DARK monster to reveal 3 Normal Traps in your Deck for your opponent to randomly choose 1 to set to your field. Alice Summons a Lady of Lament from grave on Normal Summon, she can Special herself from hand by banishing a Trap from hand or GY, and she adds a Fiend whose combined ATK and DEF equals 2000 from your Deck when Tributed or destroyed. Lilith gives you access to your Traps while Alice gets you follow-up or starts your plays on following turns. The funniest thing about Alice's effect to add a Fiend whose combined stats equals 2000 when Tributed is that you can search Libic with it. Which is why we are playing 3 Libic, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss and 2 Scarm, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss. BA's can Special themselves from hand if you control no Spell/Trap Cards, but we will not always be using that effect because they are only 1 effect per turn and only once that turn. If anything, their effects when sent to grave are what we are aiming for. Libic Specials a Level 3 DARK Fiend from your hand with its effects negated when sent to grave and Scarm adds a Level 3 DARK Fiend from your Deck during the End Phase it was sent to grave. If you Summon Libic off of Tour Guide, make a Rank 3 with them, and detach Libic, you get to Summon a Level 3 DARK Fiend from hand which can give you a Level 3 DARK Fiend monster on field for Ties of the Brethren for your Lady of Lament plays after you've done all of your Armored Xyz plays. You can Summon Tour Guide, Scarm, or Alice. Scarm and Alice will also give you additional benefits in more searches. But, you'd rather not Summon Lilith as she functionally does nothing if negated which invalidates the whole idea of getting a Level 3 DARK Fiend on field for Ties. As for Scarm, you can search Tour Guide, Alice, or Lilith for next turn which is great. Finally, 3 Tour Guide From the Underworld which Summons a Level 3 Fiend from hand or Deck with its effect negated so that you have easy Rank 3 access for your Armored Xyz plays. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Ties of the Brethren which targets a monster and summons 2 monsters from Deck with the same Type and Attribute but with different names. This is essential to the Lady of Lament portion of your Deck. 1 Armored Xyz. This equips an Xyz in grave to a monster you control, making the ATK of the equipped monster the same as the ATK of the Xyz Monster, gives it the same Attribute, and you can send it to the GY so that monster can make a second attack. The card is okay overall, even in a dedicated Armored Xyz Deck, but we are playing it in case we draw our 1-of Full Armored Xyz or if we activated Prosperity this turn. Speaking of, 3 Pot of Prosperity. 1 Trap Trick. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 2 Simul Archfiends and 1 Dimensional Barrier. Simul Archfiends makes it so that for the turn, neither player can Special Summon the same card types as they currently control (Ritual, Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, or Link) and if you don't control 2 of the same card type, all Ritual, Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, and Links you control gain 500 ATK. This card is sort of like D Barrier, but I feel like it has some more applications in different situations. First of all, it affects Links whereas D Barrier doesn't which is really nice against Link strategies. Second, if your opponent were playing an Xyz Deck, Simul Archfiends does not negate your own Armored Xyz monsters. You can use Full Armored Xyz earlier in the turn before your opponent has committed to a Ritual, Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, or Link Summon, and still have the ability to stop your opponent from going into more of their Ritual/Extra Deck plays while keeping your own Armored Xyz monsters live. Even so, we are still playing 1 D Barrier in the situation where you don't face an Xyz Deck or in the case where you only have access to the Lady of Lament portion of your Deck and need a more heavy-handed way to deal with your opponent's turn. 3 Fiend Griefing which shuffles a monster in your opponent's GY into the Deck and gives you the option of sending a Fiend from your Deck to the GY. You are usually going to be sending Scarm for an add during the End Phase, but you can optionally also play a Farfa, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss in order to have another form of monster removal. 1 Full Armored Xyz which immediately allows you to Xyz Summon if you control an Xyz Monster, and you can banish it from GY to equip an Xyz from field or GY to an Xyz you control where the equipped monster gains ATK equal to the equipped monster's ATK and if it would be destroyed, you can destroy the equip instead. 2 Transaction Rollback which pays half to copy the effect of a Normal Trap in your opponent's GY and you can pay half and banish it from GY to copy the effect of a Normal Trap in your GY. And finally, 3 Anti-Spell Fragrance to give you more insulation against certain types of Spell-based removal.

For the Extra Deck, 1 Garura, Wings of Resonant Life, 2 Elder Entity N'tss, and 1 Golden Cloud Beast - Malong for a draw, pop, or bounce when sent off of Ultimate Slayer. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder and 1 Stellar Nemesis T-PHON - Doomsday Star. 1 D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex which can be made with a D/D/D monster which is usually going to be Darius which gives you 2 activations of its effect which can detach 2 to attach an opponent's card to it as material once per chain. 1 Mereologic Aggregator for a negate when sent off of Ultimate Slayer. 1 Full Armored DARK Lancer which can be made with a Rank 5 or 6 and gains 300 ATK for each material attached to it. It can add back an Xyz card from GY every turn and if its equipped with an equip card, it can attach a monster your opponent controls to itself as material. 1 Full Armored Crystalzero Lancer which can be made with a Rank 5 WATER and it gains 500 ATK for each of its materials. If it would be destroyed, you can detach 1, and you can detach 1 to negate the effects of all face-up monsters your opponent controls for the turn. This card can give DARK Lancer more material and going second, it can negate your opponent's board for more insurance for an OTK. 1 Xyz Armor Fortress which can be made with a Rank 3 or 4 monster and it cannot be used as Xyz material if it has material. You can also detach up to 2 materials from it to add the same number of Armored Xyz cards with different names from Deck, and if its equipped to a monster, the equiped monster deals double battle damage when it battles another monster. The fact that you cannot use it as Xyz material if it has material is so annoying whic his why we have to play Armored Xyz in addition to Full Armored Xyz in order to have another card to search to detach 2 from it in the advent where you activated Prosperity for the turn and cannot detach 2 from Armor Torpedo. But this card is very important for the whole Armored Xyz line. 1 Xyz Armor Torpedo which can detach 2 to draw 1 card and if its equipped to a monster, it prevents your opponent from activating cards and effects when the equipped monster battles and also negate the effects of all face-up monsters your opponent controls until the end of the damage step, and if the equipped monster is an Xyz monster, it cannot be targeted. 1 Number 47: Nightmare Shark which can detach 1 to make a WATER you control able to attack directly for the turn. This is good for Zeus plays, but it being able to detach 1 at any point means that you can rank it up into Armor Fortress for it to detach 2 for 2 searches and have it be able to be used as Xyz Material. 1 D/D/D Stone King Darius which can be ranked up into Machinex or it can make itself be unable to be destroyed by battle and destroy the monster it battled which is good for making Zeus. Finally, 1 Unchained Soul Lord of Yama which is a send off of Ultimate Slayer as it can banish itself from GY if a card(s) you control is destroyed to Summon a Fiend from hand or GY.

Side Deck: 3 Alpha, the Master of Beasts. 1 Dinowrestler Pankratops. 3 Ultimate Slayer. 2 Ice Dragon's Prison. 3 Torrential Tribute. You can Main Deck this card, but it does conflict with your Armored Xyz monsters as you might end up destroying them or having to destroy an equipped Xyz via the effect of Full Armored Xyz to protected the equipped monster which can prevent you from OTKing on the following turn, but it isn't too great of an issue, so it is up to you whether you want to Main Deck it or not. And finally, 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: It's all about who you know
deck_description:
18 Verily I say unto you, Whatsoever ye shall bind on earth shall be bound in heaven: and whatsoever ye shall loose on earth shall be loosed in heaven.

19 Again I say unto you, That if two of you shall agree on earth as touching any thing that they shall ask, it shall be done for them of my Father which is in heaven.

20 For where two or three are gathered together in my name, there am I in the midst of them. -Matthew 18:17-20 KJV

Horse of the Floral knights has faith in what it has been given to it from God to have itself and any other material (1 light warrior in this case) have the faith to call a fusion monster onto the field due to the goodness of God. Centaur Mina can then arrive onto the field and, because of what is good from God, a level 2 monster in waiting (in the hand) or one that doesn’t want to be on the field (in the GY) can arrive onto the field and an opponent’s hidden technique can be avoided. The prophet in waiting, Silvervine Senri, can then be summoned to use the message he has from God to “have faith in His Goodness” which is used to tell a level 2 monster that it is okay to go back onto the field as well as a level 2 monster in waiting if God’s diversity can be showcased. With these monster(s) being allowed onto the field by the promises of God, they are able to support their allies in some way, call an Xyz or Synchro monster to the field, or make a spiritual connection to call a Link monster onto the field. In this example, the message from God is used to call Gigant Spright who is able to use the level 2 monster’s message from God to tell another level 2 monster to join it on the field in good faith toward God. If Hero Kid is told of this message, he can use the suit God gave him to call other Hero Kids to the field that are not in waiting or don’t want to be on the field. And the Hero Kids that received the message from God in good faith can then use that to either call Sky Calvary Centaurius to the field or make a spiritual connection to Spright Sprind to call it to the field. Sprind and Centarius can then be used to have others stay in waiting due to the goodness of God. Penguins can help by stressing the importance of staying in waiting due to the promises that God has given them via Penguin Sword and their whole archetype strategy. Slower Swallow can be used too due to the messages from God she delivers to others.

Goat Format Return deck, only this time with Fiends and primarily using Necrofear to dump things away. Return decks do struggle with balancing stuff you actually want to get rid of to benefit off the card while also making sure you don't brick, so this tries to balance a good few boss monsters with lots of consistency and destruction from everything else. Generally the deck is fine establishing field presence due to this. 

Boss monsters include Ruler for the very handy effect negation and Skull Archfiend for targetting immunity. Paying 500 every turn doesn't matter when you're going to be either going for a big push with Return or just bashing into things; plus losing life points isn't a huge issue with Return decks anyway. 

Spells include Book of Moon to recycle your Assailent/Mimics while also handling potential problem cards. Stuff like Card Destruction and Lightning Storm help run through your cards easier. 

Traps are minimalistic given the heavy focus on monsters. Phoenix Wing helps as a cost card to speed things up while everything else acts as pure fundementals to clean the field if required or disrupt plays.

Side deck is a wide assortment of potential counters to builds, either going more field-focused with backrow to Brain Control as alt-removal to the typical Mind Control/Spy plays to handle metagaming if needed.

So, something to note. This deck was not made with the intention of really winning. It can definitely can with Lava Golem, Ra or Nightingale but the aim of it was more to be an annoynce the battle against than anything else. Just a complete nightmare and upon testing, I think this deck accomplishes that quite well. 

Basically, you force winged kuriboh on the field as much as possible so you can survive the turn, then dismantle your opponents board as much as possible. Even if Winged Kuriboh gets negated, the other kuribohs can and will save you, as will Waboku

deck_excerpt: Yugi's deck from the Battle City arc
deck_description: This is definitely the largest deck, since we see Yugi duel a lot. Had to actually trim down since it breaks the 60 card maximum. Yugi uses a lot of really powerful monsters, and is lucky enough to draw weaker ones first, so I added in Delta the Magnet Warrior, Epsilon the Magnet Warrior, Imperial Bower, Joker's Straight, and Magnet Induction, to help summon his staple tributes. Included Obelisk the Tormentor and The Winged Dragon of Ra in the side deck since he earns those at the end of the Battle City tournament. Try to summon Yugi's favorite god card, Slifer the Sky Dragon!
It's a Trap...Trix!

deck_excerpt: Yugi's deck from the Duelist Kingdom arc
deck_description: All the cards Yugi uses in the Duelist Kingdom arc. Included fusion material for Zombie Warrior, which Yugi has as a normal monster. Includes Dragon Master Knight since Yugi summons that in the weird virtual world between Duelist Kingdom and Battle City. Try to summon Black Skull Dragon with a buddy in a 2 vs 2 duel. Includes Dark Sage in the side deck because it is ludicrously hard to summon and Yugi does not have Time Wizard. Summon one of the ritual monsters for victory!

deck_excerpt: Yugi's deck from the Virtual World arc

deck_excerpt: Yugi's deck from the Waking the Dragons arc

Includes Legendary Knight Critias, Legendary Knight Hermos, Legendary Knight Timaeus, Legend of Heart, The Claw of Hermos, and The Fang of Critias in the side deck since he uses those cards in his duel against Dartz, at the end of the arc. Includes The Seal of Orichalcos in his side deck since he uses it in his first duel against Raphael. Summon a Timaeus fusion for victory!

deck_excerpt: What if Aster Phoenix dueled today?
deck_description:
Aster Phoenix Deck adapted to today's format

Let me know if you know how to improve it

Standard Dragonmaid stuff with some slightly subpar cards to cut the cost down. Some fun little disruption tecs into the deck such as Time Thief Redoer, Harpie's Feather Duster, and Mirror Force for nostalgia's sake. The goal here was to make Dragonmaids the actual focus of the deck rather than just a secondary win condition. Keep in mind this is mostly just for fun and your results will liekly not be as good as the "most optimal" strategy. You could probably create a pretty good side deck with minimal effort, but I wanted to keep this as cheap as possible, but still able to occasionally perform really well against more "meta" decks.

I was considering doing some sort of Sacred Beast thing with Lady of Lament when I saw Three-Eyed Ghost and realized how it could search Raviel, Lord of Phantasms and Raviel, Lord of Phantasms - Shimmering Scraper, but as it turns out that the only benefit to playing Raviel and Shimmering Scraper is making use of Lair of Darkness for Raviel's ATK-gaining effect by Tributing a monster and Shimmering Scraper adding itself back by Tributing a monster in addition to their big ATK stats and OTK potential via Shimmering Scraper targeting Raviel. On the other hand, Uria, Lord of Searing Flames functionally has similar, if not better OTK potential while also giving you the ability to make better use of Hyper Blaze rather than having to rely on 2 hard-to-summon monsters. This Deck intends to use cards like Dark Beckoning Beast and Opening of the Spirit Gates to get you a Chaos Core on the field, which gives you a Level 3 DARK Fiend Target for Ties of the Brethren while also allowing you to set up a Uria OTK with Hyper Blaze on your following turn or a bit later.

For monsters: 3 Lord of the Heavenly Prison which can reveal itself in hand to give all of your Set cards destruction protection, and if you activate a set Spell/Trap from hand, and if it was revealed already, you can set a Spell/Trap from Deck. First off, giving protection to your backrow is already such a good effect, but in this Deck, specifically, since we want to try to OTK with Uria on your following turn, Lord can set Hyper Blaze from your Deck to set-up the OTK for your following turn. 1 Uria, Lord of Searing Flames. It needs to be Specialed from hand by sending 3 face-up Traps you control to grave and gains 1000 ATK for each Continuous Trap in your GY, and it can destroy a set Spell/Trap every turn. You are never hard-Summoning this card. We are usually getting this out from GY with Hyper Blaze ignoring its Summoning Conditions. 3 Lilith, Lady of Lament which can Tribute a monster to have your opponent choose 1 of 3 Normal Traps of your choice to set from Deck. 3 Alice, Lady of Lament which can Summon back a Lady of Lament from GY on Normal Summon, it can banish a Trap from hand or GY to Special itself from hand, and if it's Tributed, it can add a Fiend whose ATK and DEF equals 2000 when combined which gives you access to Lilith for next turn. 1 Chaos Core. It is a bit of a strange card as it is essentially pretty bad, even though it was released in 2020 in the Sacred Beast Structure Deck. It essentially is supposed to set-up Dimension Fusion Destruction as it sends up to 1 each of Raviel, Hamon, and Uria from hand and/or Deck to GY if its targeted by an attack or effect to place a Phantasm Counter on itself for each which prevents battle damage and prevents it from being destroyed. However, it has a different use in this Deck. For 1, it is a Level 3 DARK Fiend target for Ties of the Brethren on field. Since Beckoning Beast gives you an extra normal for this card, you can Link them off for a Link-2 and Summon back Chaos Core with Spirit Gates, giving you a Level 3 DARK Fiend on field with a Link-2 for more interaction and/or interruption on your opponent's turn. Also, since Ties targets Chaos Core, it can send a Uria from Deck to put it into rotation for Hyper Blaze to bring it back next turn. 3 Dark Beckoning Beast which adds a Uria, Hamon, or Raviel or a card that mentions one of them from your Deck on Normal Summon. Also, it gives you an extra Normal of a Fiend with 0 ATK and DEF. Again, this gives you access to Chaos Core on field for a Link play for Spirit Gates to bring back Chaos Core. Finally, 1 Tour Guide From the Underworld for an Xyz play in a tight spot.

For Spell/Traps: 3 Opening of the Spirit Gates. On activation, it searches Uria, Hamon, or Raviel or a monster that mentions one of them from Deck. As a soft OPT, it can discard a card to Special Summon a Fiend from GY with 0 ATK and DEF. This gets you back Chaos Core after a Link play for a target on field for Ties, of course. And it's third effect adds back a Continuous Spell from GY if you control a Level 10 monster which is not relevant in this Deck. 3 Ties of the Brethren which Summons 2 monsters from Deck with the same Type, Attribute, and Level as a targeted monster you control. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Transaction Rollback which pays half your Life Points to copy the effect of a Normal Trap in your opponent's GY and can banish itself from GY and pay half to copy the effect of a Normal Trap in your GY. Because Spirit Gates discards to bring back a Fiend, it give you the opportunity to discard Transaction Rollback to have access to its GY effect which is much better in this Deck. The same goes for Hyper Blaze's effect to discard a card to bring back a Sacred Beast. 3 Archfiend's Ghastly Glitch which targets a card on field and destroys it if you control a Fiend and gives you the option of sending a Fiend from Deck to GY afterwards. 1 Trap Trick. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 1 Dimensional Barrier. 3 Torrential Tribute. 2 Hyper Blaze which makes Uria's Summoning Conditions able to send face-down Traps you control. Also, once per battle, it can send a Trap from hand or Deck to the GY to make the ATK/DEF of a Uria you control become equal to the number of Traps on field and in GY x1000 for the rest of the turn which is great for OTKing. And it can discard a card to bring back a Sacred Beast. We will be going through plenty of Traps in a Lady of Lament Deck, and this card allows you to easily Summon Uria while also making it a great OTK tool.

Extra Deck: 1 Garura, Wings of Resonant Life, 1 Fossil Warrior Skull Knight, 2 Elder Entity N'tss, 1 Golden Cloud Beast - Malong, and 1 Mereologic Aggregator for Ultimate Slayer and Dogmatika Punishment targets. Garura draws a card, Skull Knight can banish itself from GY to destroy a monster on field, N'tss destroys a card when sent to GY, Malong bounces a face-up card your opponent controls, and Aggregator negates the effects of a face-up card your opponent controls. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Stellar Nemesis T-PHON - Doomsday Star. 1 D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex which can be made with any D/D/D monster and it can detach 2 cards when your opponent's monster card activates its effect and attaches it to this card. 1 Downerd Magician for more Zeus material. 1 D/D/D Stone King Darius which can be ranked up into Machinex or protect itself during battle for you to easily make Zeus. 1 Number 49: Fortune Tune to make Zeus, 1 Unchained Soul Lord of Yama which can be send off of Ultimate Slayer or Punishment as it can banish itself from GY when a card(s) you control is destroyed to Summon a Fiend from hand or GY. 1 S:P Little Night and 1 I:P Masquerena for your Link play options.

Side Deck: 3 Kashtira Fenrir. 1 Dinowrestler Pankratops. 3 Ultimate Slayer. 1 Simul Archfiends. 3 Evenly Matched. 2 Dogmatika Punishment. 2 Ice Dragon's Prison.

A fun control/OTK deck. Vulnerable to backrow removal.

OTK move: "Mad Mauler" reduce level of a Level 8 (Doomking, Mazera,...) Synchro with it to Shogunsaga, which banishes Changshi, which revives herself from banishment then sent a Mezuki to revive another Zombie. Total ATK: Shogunsaga: 5000 + Changshi: 2000 + ATK of the one revived by Mezuki.

Prefer target for Glow-Up Bloom: Changshi. She sends "Mad Mauler" to GY. "Mauler" eats two level from Changshi and Synchro with her to "Immortal Dragon", then send another Zombie to GY (Mazera, Doomking).

You can replace Trap Card in this deck with your prefered ones (Foolish Burial, Hand Traps). I used many Traps because I like playing mind game.

deck_excerpt: -4 for opponent first turn (fair and balanced format)
deck_description:
....so yeah no one is gonna like you playing this. I've always been a fan of Gravekeepers since probably the GX days, they've just never carried a good reputation with them. Playing them in a combo-heavy format like Edison will cause some rage, especially with how busted Gravekeepers can be with the right setup. 

For one, Necrovalley is extremely dangerous; even with the Edison rules meaning that it can be destroyed with a simple field spell it's still one of the most oppressive effects out there despite the confusing errata texts. Most meta/good Edison builds require Graveyard access to some degree and removing that shuts a lot of them down from the get-go while turning all of your monsters into either super dangerous beatsticks or annoying walls that can't be easily smashed through. Generally as a Gravekeeper player you want to keep it active as much as humanly possible, so we use numerous protections to do this; Starlight is a obvious one, but this can be played around, so Spell-Shield is used as a secondary alongside a copy of Judgment of Anubis to handle single-target destruction options to keep them guessing.

Royal Tribute WILL win you games from the first turn if you draw right. Seeing as Edison deck metas generally have a lot more focus on monsters than backrow activating a first turn Tribute generally means minimal loss of 2 cards, though for me I was getting 3/4 more often and even managed to completely wipe out a hand or two. It's not only free infomation on the opponent, it's just disgustingly uninteractable. 

Other than that, this deck mostly plays like a usual Gravekeeper deck of the time, focused around field control and slower play. Generally you want to be in a position where your defence lets the opponent make mistakes and allows you to spring on them with horrible backrow negates and huge monster values. I guess what makes Gravekeepers so great is that you can play both offence and defence and the deck doesn't really suffer for it as a whole. With Commandment/Spy/Stele and Allure you also get a ton of consistency + recovery, being able to reliably get your critical pieces over and over. 

Side-deck is based around whatever is being played, including some conventional counters, more consistency, or trying to deal with a specific style or combo. Nothing much else to say.
