deck_name: Master Duel - KASHTIRA deck prepares for banlist update - How to play after Number 89 is banned?
deck_description: Master Duel's upcoming banlist number 89 will be banned. In addition, currently Kashtira Arise-Heart has not been updated to the game. Today I will review for you a combo as well as cards that can support the deck to play well after the banlist and wait for Kashtira Arise-Heart to be updated into the game. I put my deck profile below the video description for everyone to refer to.

deck_excerpt: "The empire, long divided, must unite; long united, must divide. Thus it has ever been"
deck_description:
=Ancient Warriors=

Ancient Warriors are a Beast-Warrior Archetype (Fire Formation - Tenki) introduced in Ignition Assault, based on the novel War of the Three Kingdoms, it features warriors of the aforementioned kingdoms and their journeys. This is a going second strategy that focuses on OTK'ing and depleting resources via their high stats and effects.

=Main Deck=

Starting with the Wind Attribute Ancient Warriors, representing the Shu Han, Ancient Warriors - Virtuous Liu Xuan is the second best starter for the Deck. Summoning 1 Ancient Warrior by sending 1 card from hand or Field to the GY (this is a very common cost, get used to it), enabling you to then summon Ancient Warriors - Masterful Sun Mou which, like Liu, can summon from Deck, granting you a Link-2 and combo extension which the Deck needs a lot. During any battle involving an Ancient Warriors he can draw you 1 card, which does come up quite often allowing you to get a handtrap or breaker that will help you cripple your already weakened opponent. Liu Xan can 100% be played at 1 copy granted you are on triple Fire Formation - Tenki or you feel lucky.

Unlike Liu, Ancient Warriors - Ingenious Zhuge Kong is a card you don't want to see in your opening hand but instead in your endboard as he is a crucial piece of interaction for the Deck, summoning himself when added by an Ancient Warrior card effect he can negate Spells/Traps by sending Ancient Warrior continuous Spells/Traps, which your most important does have a grave effect which makes it not a very absurd cost. He can negate monsters but only if Liu Xuan is on the board, which most of the time he is not.

Ancient Warriors - Loyal Guan Yun unfortunately wasn't the next Dinowrestler Pankratops but instead he is one of your best baits, protecting the other Warriors from card effects making Sun and Liu not dead on arrival, while having a neat summoning condition which does contradict with cards like Change of Heart or Triple Tactics Talent's steal effect so watch out for that, and a pop on top of all of this. This guy can help you break boards with ease while giving you Link material.  

Ancient Warriors - Valiant Zhang De on the other hand is your best OTK tools, being searcheable by Ancient Warriors - Savage Don Ying or Ancient Warriors Oath - Double Dragon Lords, he can be summoned by controling at least 2 Ancient Warriors, on board he gains 300ATK for each monster your opponent control, which paired with his ability to attack up to 2 monsters means he can dish big ammounts of damage very easily. This effect by the way must be activated in the Main Phase, I kept mistaking it for the longest time as something that comes up during the Battle Phase...

  

Ancient Warriors - Masterful Sun Mou is the Deck's true starter if you don't count Tenyi. Having the same condition as Liu of sending a card to summon an Ancient Warrior from Deck and unlike Liu when another Ancient Warrior effect is activated he becomes a Compulsory Evacuation Device. If you start with Sun you will have to summon the Liu or any other Wind Ancient Warrior since its a requirement for their Link or using Ancient Warriors Saga - Deception and Betrayal's effect to change the Attribute which is not recommended.

Ancient Warriors - Fearsome Zhang Yuan is an oddball, the fire Ancient Warriors are focused on battle which doesn't help you build boards, him and Ancient Warriors - Ambitious Cao De can be alternated over. The first summons himself for free if your Ancient Warrior is about to battle, lowering the attack of the target by 1000ATK points and if a card is destroyed by battle or card effect he can pop a card on board. While Cao De summons himself for a send after a card is destroyed by battle, and when he destroys a monster by battle he gets to summon it back to your board... in Def position cause we cant have nice things. I hardly search for these guys and at one point just cut them off.

One of the only Dark Monsters in the Archetype, Ancient Warriors - Rebellious Lu Feng is a crucial endboard piece, summoning himself if you control the highest attack Ancient Warrior on board. Now you might be thinking: "Are they expecting an Ancient Warrior mirror match?" and the answer to that is maybe but most likely its because of Lu Feng's last effect that changes control if your opponent controls a monster with high attack, you can however fetch him back with Ancient Warriors Saga - Deception and Betrayal but at that point he was probably linked away. The effect you will be using the most however is his ability to pop the highest attack monster on board, which does lock you into Ancient Warrior effects, which emans you cannot use anything prior that isnt an Ancient Warrior, otherwise you cannot pop. You will be searching him via Don or Double Dragon Lords.

Ancient Warriors - Savage Don Ying is a Trickstar card if Trickstars were good. This card cares about you controling Level 7 or higher Ancient Warriors which enables his taxation effect which makes the opponent pay 400LP for every activation, he cares so much about this that on summon he gets to search a Level 7 or Higer Warrior or a Continuous Spell/Trap. his last effect synergizes with the one you are meant to search and have on board with him, Ancient Warriors - Rebellious Lu Feng, that whenever a card hits the GY he gets to banish something from there. Meaning you get to remove a card via Lu Feng, bounce via Sun Mou and then banish something in the GY with Ying.

Ancient Warriors Oath - Double Dragon Lords is another crucial piece for the endboard, boosting your monsters by 500 points while giving you a search on summon which allows you to get Ancient Warriors Saga - Deception and Betrayal in you need to bring out Don or getting you Lu Feng/Zhuge for extra interruption. The effect this card is known for is the bounce by sending a card from field or hand, which can be used to trigger the backrow to summon whatever you may have searchead 

Ancient Warriors Saga - Deception and Betrayal brings the bricks out of your hand by paying LP equal to their Level x 100, you will mostly be summon Don Ying with this unless you believe Stormforth Ancient Warriors is the future. The niche control + Attribute change effect is here so you can get back your Lu Feng, it also allows the Deck to go into Bahamut Shark to access Toadally Awesome. Currently at 3 but running it at 1-2 doesn't sound that bad.

Ancient Warriors Saga - Three Visits is one of the cards that you always want to see, searching an Ancient Warrior of different name when another is summoned, giving you access to Zhuge without you having to waste Double Dragon's effect or searcing Valiant for extra bodies for the OTK. This card also has the GY effect of summoning a Warrior from hand when sent from Field which makes Double, Zhunge, Liu and Sun less costly.

=Combo Example=

Hand: Fire Formation - Tenki or Ancient Warriors - Masterful Sun Mou and 1 card

Fire Formation - Tenki activate > Tenki add Ancient Warriors - Masterful Sun Mou > Sun Mou normal summon > Sun Mou sends Tenki for Ancient Warriors - Ingenious Zhuge Kong > Zhuge summons himself > make Double Dragon Lords adding Ancient Warriors - Rebellious Lu Feng, Summon Lu Feng.

If you have Ancient Warriors Saga - Three Visits on hand you can activate it before Tenki, summoning the Sun will make it add Ancient Warriors - Savage Don Ying, which you will search Ancient Warriors Saga - Deception and Betrayal for instead of the Lu Feng, pay 600LP to summon Don which will search the Lu Feng.

The Deck doesnt have big combos since its mostly based on what you have, being a more free form Deck.

deck_name: A King's Guide to Red Dragon Archfiend (October 2023)
deck_excerpt: Make competitive use of your x3 "Crimson King" structure deck and your opponents will feel your ABSOLUTE POWERFORCE!
deck_description:
Hello King (or Queen), you've come to the right strategy guide to make competitive use of your x3 Crimson King Structure deck.

The "Crimson King" structure deck has finally released for the TCG on September 21st, and I decided to buy x3 of the product for myself to test out the new cards. To my surprise, the deck is surprisingly resilient, explosive, powerful and most importantly, FUN! In my humble opinion, I'd say the Crimson King structure deck gives you as much competitive bang for your buck as the Albaz and Traptrix structure decks, I highly recommend you folks get it too!

Red Dragon Archfiend now has 9 one card combos, and an additional 6 ways to two-card combo, making the deck extremely consistent - on par with other synchro strategies like Swordsoul and P.U.N.K. This allows the strategy to fit in a whopping 18+ non-engine cards and still be playable! As a result, this deck can confidently play through minor handtraps like Ash Blossom and Impermanence. High impact handtraps such as Nibiru and Droll can be shrugged off as well!
 
The deck also works and melds incredibly well with Bystials very much like Dragonlink, netting you additional resources, interruption, extenders, beatsticks and combo pieces. 
 
Not only Jack Atlas one of my favourite duelists of all time from the anime (loooove his beautiful accent and arrogant bluster), now his deck is sufficiently powerful to become a rogue meta contender! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

Red Dragon Archfiend is optimally played with the Bystial cards, since they support each other exceptionally well. 
 
The RED DRAGON ARCHFIEND cards comprise the main core of this deck, comprising of 18 cards. Your 10 one card combo starters are x3 Soul Resonator, x3 Resonator Call, x3 Crimson Gaia and x1 Foolish Burial (Send Vision Resonator, search Crimson Gaia). You have 6 conditional two card combo starters and they are x3 Vision Resonator (has to be sent to GY to search Crimson Gaia, starting combo) and x3 Bone Archfiend (sends to GY Vision Resonator, searching Crimson Gaia, starting combo). 
 
The BYSTIAL cards comprise the main core of this deck, comprising of 8 cards. The Bystial cards fulfill many functions - they are resource generation, interruption, extenders, beatsticks and combo pieces. Branded Regained and Branded Beast are incredible cards to have in the backrow and have inherent synergy with Red Dragon Archfiend synchro monsters. In the sidedeck, you have a searchable floodgate Branded Etude which acts as a "Macro Cosmos," banishing your opponent's material for an Extra Deck/Ritual summon. 
 
The rest of the cards are STAPLE cards. TT Talent, TT Thrust, Called By, Ash Blossoms, Imperms function very well in this meta due to the prevalence of handtraps. Droplet is used since Kashtira Ariseheart is gone and Red Dragon Archfiend/Bystial cards love being sent to the GY. 
 
In the SIDE DECK x3 Crossouts with it's respective targets are present since your opponents are likely to side in Droll (Droll hurts this deck a lot) and Dimensional Barrier in games 2/3. Archfiend Eccentrick is searchable S/T destruction with Soul Resonator. Red Resonator is used to win in time since it gains you lifepoints (yeah that's right this card is used competitively in a non-Spright deck for once). x3 Anti-Spell is the strongest card this deck can use going first, since it doesn't conflict directly with the spells in this strategy.  
 

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN

 

Being a synchro deck, Red Dragon Archfiend is inherently combo-focused. This strategy features several combos, and they are resilient and can pivot to another direction depending on the gamestate (For example, this deck can play through high impact handtraps like Nibiru, or if certain chokepoints like Red Rising Dragon and Crimson Resonator are negated/interrupted). This strategy has many combos, but I'll just feature the three I like to use. 

 

Here is the deck's bread-and-butter 1 card combo: 

 

Crimson Gaia = Bystial Dispater (Monster negate or destroy) + Hot Red Dragon Archfiend (Omni-negate any card on opponent's field) + Red Zone (Targeted destuction, summons Dark Dragon Synchro from banished) + Crimson Gaia (follow-up search and summons Red Dragon Archfiend if a monster is destroyed) + Soul Resonator in GY (destruction protection) + Bone Archfiend in GY (follow-up) + Synkron Resonator (follow-up).

 

  1. Activate Crimson Gaia. Search Soul Resonator. 
  2. Normal summon Soul Resonator. Search Bone Archfiend. 
  3. Special summon Bone Archfiend from hand by sending a card from hand/field to GY. (For a true 1 card combo, you'd send Crimson Gaia, but typically you have other cards in hand to send since it is ideal to keep Crimson Gaia on field). 
  4. Activate Bone Archfiend's level modification effect targeting Soul Resonator reducing it's level by 1 making level 2. Send from deck to GY Crimson Resonator. (If Crimson Resonator is already in GY, send Uvualoop instead). 
  5. Synchro summon Red Rising Dragon using Bone Archfiend + Soul Resonator. 
  6. Red Rising Dragon summons from GY Crimson Resonator. 
  7. Activate Crimson Resonator's effect to summon Vision Resonator and Synkron Resonator from deck. 
  8. Synchro summon Scarred Dragon Archfiend using Crimson Resonator + Red Rising Dragon. 
  9. Synchro summon Bystial Dispater using Scarred Dragon Archfiend + Vision Resonator. 
  10. CL1 Vision Resonator to search Red Zone, CL2 Scarred Dragon Archfiend to special summon (counts as synchro summon) Red Dragon Archfiend from Extra Deck.
  11. Synchro summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend using Red Dragon Archfiend + Synkron Resonator. 
  12. Activate Synkron Resonator's effect to add from GY a resonator from GY (Soul Resonator for follow-up next turn or Vision Resonator tuner extender). 
  13. Summon any other extenders, summon additional Dark Synchro Dragon monsters (Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend can negate S/T during battle phase, like Evenly Matched or summon another Scarred Dragon since it floats and is "Red Dragon Archfiend" on the field turning on Red Zone). Set your spells/traps, especially Red Zone. 
Even if your opponent manages to clear your entire field, your GY is set up with Bone Archfiend and your hand has Soul Resonator + more so you can repeat the same thing next turn. I'd say this deck's combo potential, resource generation and explosive power is comparable to Dragonlink! 
 
Here is what to do if you've been Nibiru'd. This requires extenders in the form of Bone Archfiend and any Bystial. 
 

HELP! (I'VE BEEN NIBIRU'D!) Crimson Gaia + Bystial + Bone Archfiend = Bystial Dispater (Monster negate or destroy) + Scarred Dragon Archfiend (Presence on-field turns on Red Zone, floats into OG Red Dragon Archfiend), Red Zone (Targeted destuction, summons Dark Dragon Synchro from banished) + Crimson Gaia (follow-up search and summons Red Dragon Archfiend if a monster is destroyed) + Soul Resonator in GY (destruction protection) + Bone Archfiend in GY (follow-up) + Synkron Resonator (follow-up).

 

 
  1. Activate Crimson Gaia. Search Soul Resonator. 
  2. Normal summon Soul Resonator. Search Obsessive Uvualoop. 
  3. Special summon Bone Archfiend from hand by sending a card from hand/field to GY. (For a true 1 card combo, you'd send Crimson Gaia, but typically you have other cards in hand to send since it is ideal to keep Crimson Gaia on field). 
  4. Activate Bone Archfiend's level modification effect targeting Soul Resonator reducing it's level by 1 making level 2. Send from deck to GY Crimson Resonator. (If Crimson Resonator is already in GY, send Uvualoop instead). 
  5. Synchro summon Red Rising Dragon using Bone Archfiend + Soul Resonator. 
  6. Red Rising Dragon summons from GY Crimson Resonator. 
  7. Activate Crimson Resonator's effect to summon Vision Resonator and Synkron Resonator from deck. (AT THIS POINT, TYPICALLY OPPONENTS NIBIRU SINCE THIS IS THE 5TH SUMMON)
  8. CL1 Synkron Resonator to add Vision Resonator back to hand, CL2 Vision Resonator to search Red Zone. 
  9. Special summon Bystial, banishing Crimson Resonator from GY. 
  10. Special summon Vision Resonator from hand, since you control a level 5 or higher monster (the Bystial). 
  11. Special summon Uvualoop from hand, banishing Red Rising Dragon in GY. 
  12. Synchro summon Bystial Dis Pater using Bystial + Uvualoop. 
  13. Activate Bystial Dis Pater's effect to special summon from banished Red Rising Dragon. 
  14. Synchro summon Scarred Dragon Archfiend using Vision Resonator + Red Rising Dragon. 
  15. Summon any other extenders, summon additional Dark Synchro Dragon monsters (Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend can negate S/T during battle phase, like Evenly Matched or summon another Scarred Dragon since it floats and is "Red Dragon Archfiend" on the field turning on Red Zone). Set your spells/traps, especially Red Zone. 
The endboard isn't as good as the first combo since you've been interrupted by Nibiru, but it's more or less the same! Everything is present except for Hot Red Dragon Archfiend's on-field omni-negate. 
 


One of the best endboards, featuring Bystial Lubellion and the one card combo: 

Bystial Lubellion + Crimson Gaia = Bystial Dispater (Monster negate or destroy) + Hot Red Dragon Archfiend (Omni-negate any card on opponent's field) + Scarred Dragon Archfiend (Presence on-field turns on Red Zone, floats into OG Red Dragon Archfiend) + Red Zone (Targeted destuction, summons Dark Dragon Synchro from banished) + Crimson Gaia (follow-up search and summons Red Dragon Archfiend if a monster is destroyed) + Soul Resonator in GY (destruction protection) + Bone Archfiend in GY (follow-up) + Synkron Resonator (follow-up) + Branded Beast (Targeted destruction) + Branded Regained (+1 draw when a card is banished, summon Bystial from GY).

 

  1. Activate Crimson Gaia. Search Soul Resonator. 
  2. Normal summon Soul Resonator. Search Bone Archfiend. 
  3. Special summon Bone Archfiend from hand by sending a card from hand/field to GY. (For a true 1 card combo, you'd send Crimson Gaia, but typically you have other cards in hand to send since it is ideal to keep Crimson Gaia on field). 
  4. Activate Bone Archfiend's level modification effect targeting Soul Resonator reducing it's level by 1 making level 2. Send from deck to GY Crimson Resonator. (If Crimson Resonator is already in GY, send Uvualoop instead). 
  5. Synchro summon Red Rising Dragon using Bone Archfiend + Soul Resonator. 
  6. Red Rising Dragon summons from GY Crimson Resonator. 
  7. Activate Crimson Resonator's effect to summon Vision Resonator and Synkron Resonator from deck. 
  8. Synchro summon Scarred Dragon Archfiend using Crimson Resonator + Red Rising Dragon. 
  9. Activate Bystial Lubellion's effect to search for Bystial Saronir. 
  10. Activate Bystial Saronir's effect to summon itself banishing Crimson Resonator from GY. 
  11. Summon Lubellion from GY tributing Scarred Dragon Archfiend. 
  12. Activate Scarred Dragon Archfriend's effect to special summon (counts as synchro summon) Red Dragon Archfiend from Extra Deck.
  13. Activate Lubellion's effect to place Branded Beast on your backrow. 
  14. Synchro summon Bystial Dispater using Bystial Lubellion + Vision Resonator. 
  15. Vision Resonator searches Red Zone since it was sent to GY. 
  16. Synchro summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend using Red Dragon Archfiend + Synkron Resonator. 
  17. Activate Synkron Resonator's effect to add from GY a resonator from GY (Soul Resonator for follow-up next turn or Vision Resonator tuner extender). 
  18. Synchro summon a second Scarred Dragon Archfiend using Bystial Saronir + Crimson Resonator. 
  19. Activate Saronir's effect in the GY since it left the field. Send Branded Regained to the GY. 
  20. Summon any other extenders, summon additional Dark Synchro Dragon monsters (Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend can negate S/T during battle phase, like Evenly Matched or summon another Scarred Dragon since it floats and is "Red Dragon Archfiend" on the field turning on Red Zone). Set your spells/traps, especially Red Zone. 
  21. In the End Phase, Branded Beast places Branded Regained on your backrow. 
As you can see, there are many combos and variants in the Red Dragon Archfiend deck. There are more combos than listed in this strategy guide, but I only featured three. I suggest you check out other Youtube videos, practice for yourself, and cook your own playstyles! There is so much complexity and potential that this powerful strategy can now do!
 

 

GENERAL TIPS

  • Good cards to consider for the side deck that this deck can abuse is Eradicator Epidemic Virus (and the other virus cards), since it's an insta-win vs. certain decks.
  • Red Dragon Archfiend's usual endboard can negate Dark Ruler No More and Forbidden Droplet (if they didn't send a trap)! When your opponent activates Dark Ruler/Droplet, CL2 Red Zone to pop a card, then CL3 Hot Red Dragon Archfiend's effect to negate the card. Pretty snazzy eh? Not every deck can use a monster to negate Dark Ruler/Droplet!
  • Try to leave Soul Resonator in the GY after your combo, it is destruction protection while you control any synchro monster that mentions Red Dragon Archfiend!
  • Try to set up your banished pile with a card so that Bystial Dispater can at least use it's destruction effect! Sometimes depending on your cards Bystial Dispater's destroy/negation effect won't be live. The best cards to set up the banished piles are Bystials and Obsessive Uvualoop. 
  • Obsessive Uvualoop is an incredible extender in this deck. It's also searchable as part of this deck's combo (for example, if you already have Crimson Resonator, you can search for Uvualoop). This card can banish multiple synchro monsters at the end of the regular combo so that Dispater can summon them from the banished pile, while setting up Dispater's destroy/negation! 
  • Bystials do an incredible job of cracking boards and forcing interaction from your opponent. Resolve Bystial cards first before moving on to your main combo! Remember, all you have to do is resolve Crimson Gaia/Soul Resonator and you're off to the races!
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

 

Make competitive use of your x3 "Crimson King" structure deck and your opponents will feel your ABSOLUTE POWERFORCE!

Konami has really been killing it with strong structure decks in the TCG - with the deck strong enough for competition almost right out ot the box! My additions to the structure deck cards aim to make Red Dragon Archfiend as competitive as possible with the Bystial engine and plethora of staples designed to counter the current meta.
 
In the words of the non-playable card from the structure deck - Everyone's King:

"A foolish king once forsook his land and friends, but his scarred soul was saved by a compassionate heart. He who has determined to live his own destiny shall save the world and become the true king, giver of happiness and loved by all."

Jack Atlas and his red minions has truly reached his peak form with the Crimson King structure deck. I can confidently now say that THE KING IS BACK BABY!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Dragunity, OTK, Combo, Banish, Duel Terminal
deck_description:
Dragunity is a Deck which is well known for Dragon Ravine and Dragunity Knight - Romulus but did you know they have more then just these 2 cards? It's frustrating to see how nobody aims to built a pure variant nowadays even so recent support made that exact variant so much stronger. That's why I take up the task of introducing a pure Dragunity variant to you today, let's look into the Details to find out why they are so strong: 


Researching the Dragunity Tribe history

First of all this Archetype's general Goal is to equip Small Dragon tuners to Winged Beast Monsters who then become their riders by Synchro summoning into a Dragunity Knight. A rather new focus is Banishing cards too. Very simply put that's what Dragunity is all about. 

The interesting part now is all the little interactions inbetween the Archetype that make it so unique and a one of a kind archetype. Unlike many other Duel Terminal 1 Archetype's this one has been good since it's dawn thanks to an early Structure Deck release. Now let's take a look at all the small Details:


Arriving at the hidden Ravine in Mist Valley

Getting started in this Deck is not difficult. Use cards like Dragunity Arma Mystletainn , Dragunity Legatus , Dragunity Senatus , Dragunity Remus , Dragon Ravine , Dragunity Divine Lance , Dragunity Whirlwind or Dragunity Glow to get things easily into motion in some kind of way. Since we look at least at 23 different starters within the Maindeck alone you can imagine that getting started is not a problem with this Deck. And that is not even counting in more convoluted starters like Dragunity Militum.

At this point I want to mention the L1 Winged Beast Dragunity Tribus who didn't make the cut in this Decklist but is yet another way to get things started. He can mill Dragunity Remus who can then revive itself and setup a Link-2 play easily. He's not bad but other starters felt a little more versatile and useful to me while testing out this Deck in a Master Duel environment. 

I know that people also like to use Dragunity Phalanx who is just like Dragunity Couse but in terms of a pure variant he's also just worse. Dragunity Phalanx is generic and that's the biggest reason to use him but Dragunity Couse is straightup better in this pure variant. 

There are some other Dragunity Monsters like Dragunity Corsesca (Who is good) and Spells who didn't make it into the final list mostly because they are kinda outdated or don't fit into the bigger strategy for this Deck.

Enough of badmouthing cool cards for now. After knowing how to get started we analyze every Maindeck Monster and Spell/Trap next. Prepare yourself for a lot of text (I really try to keep it short). 


The Riders, The Small Dragons & The Big Dragons

Dragunity Monsters can be put into 4 Categories. The Winged Beast non tuners, the Dragon tuners, the Dragon non tuners and the Dragunity Knights who are mostly the bosses. We start with the Winged Beast riders first. I won't mention many limitations while explaining since we play this Deck pure anyway and we don't have to care about any of these: 

Dragunity Primus Pilus is a L5 with 2200/1600 Statline. When he's Normal or Special summoned you can target a Winged Beast and equip it with a L3 or lower Dragon from your Deck. This effect can miss timing but he fulfills various roles in this Deck. He's the only L5 Winged Beast which makes him the only way to access the L8 Synchro Dragunity Knight - Barcha with the effect of Dragunity Whirlwind. Furthermore he's the strongest banishing target for Dragunity Knight - Gae Bulg to bring him up to 4200 ATK if he attacks. With an equipped Dragunity Brandistock he could even reach 6000 ATK on a followup attack which is even better and that's not even counting in cards like Dragunity Divine Lance. The last important part is the loop potential with Dragunity Legion. With that card you can use the effect of Dragunity Primus Pilus every turn and setup easy L6, 7 or 8 Synchro plays or Link-2 lines. Lorewise he's the rider of Dragunity Knight - Trident.

Dragunity Militum is a L4 with 1700/1200 Statline. Once per turn she can Special summon a Dragunity Card from the Spell & Trap Zone to your field. She's the only Dragunity Card which can special summon your equipped Dragunity Cards in Attack Position back to the field which is kinda important to have if you equipped big Beaters like Dragunity Knight - Ascalon to something on the field. She also turns into an starter if you also have Dragunity Aklys in your hand. Normal summon Dragunity Aklys and special Dragunity Militum, then use her effect to special Dragunity Aklys and you just got a Link-2 or L6 Synchro summon setup. Lorewise she's the rider of Dragunity Knight - Vajrayana.

Dragunity Dux is a L4 with 1500/1000 Statline. He gains additional 200 ATK for every Dragunity Card under your Control. When normal summoned he can equip a L3 or lower Dragon from the GY to himself. He can kinda easily reach 3700 ATK through his effect alone which is kinda ridiculous and is a good option to get things started with Dragon Ravine combined or to get a situation back in your favor. The most optimal target for these kind of effects is almost always Dragunity Couse since he can special summon himself directly on the field afterwards. Lorewise he's the rider of Dragunity Knight - Gae Bulg and later Dragunity Knight - Ascalon too. 

Dragunity Legatus is a L4 with 1800/1200 Statline. He can be special summoned if Dragon Ravine and/or any Dragunity Monster is on the field. Also if you have a Dragunity Monster in the Spell & Trap Zone you can target any Spell/Trap on the field and destroy it. Both effects are HOPT's (Hard Once per Turns). He's important since he can get things into motion without wasting your normal summon especially with Dragunity Remus combined and even has a built in removal that could even get rid of your own backrow if there's something you need in the GY to make space. As example you could destroy your Dragunity Aklys to get a free removal or Dragunity Knight - Luin to change the equip target. Lorewise he's the rider of Dragunity Knight - Areadbhair.

Dragunity Senatus is a L4 with 1800/600 Statline. By discarding one Dragunity card as a cost he can equip a Dragunity tuner Monster from the Deck to himself. If a Dragunity Card(s) would be destroyed by Battle or Card effect you can destroy a card equipped to Dragunity Senatus instead. The first effect is a HOPT. He's maybe the most simple Starter you can find monster wise. If you equip Dragunity Couse you easily reach a L10 Synchro play from that position. Since he equips directly from the Deck he and cards with similar effects are all unaffected by cards like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring too which is even better. Furthermore he has a quite useful protection effect which makes Dragunity Aklys a interesting equip choice in mid to late game too, for protection and removal at the same time. Lorewise he's the rider of Dragunity Knight - Luin.

Dragunity Legionnaire is a L3 with 1200/800 Statline. Just like Dragunity Dux he can on normal summon equip a L3 or lower Dragon from GY to himself. Unlike Dux however he can send a Dragunity card from the Spell & Trap Zone to the GY to target and destroy an opponents Monster without a once per turn. Using him after cards like Dragunity Knight - Barcha brought many Dragunity Cards into the Spell & Trap Zone is very effective. He also enables easy L7 Synchro lines with Dragunity Couse combined and is an all around good helper in many Situations. Lorewise he's the rider of Dragunity Knight - Gae Dearg.

Just to finish the rider lore Dragunity Angusticlavii which we won't ever play is the rider of Dragunity Knight - Barcha. Both Dragunity Knight - Gormfaobhar and it's older counterpart Dragunity Knight - Romulus may have Dragunity Legatus as a rider but that's not 100% confirmed. 

Now let's continue with the small Dragons which are also all Dragon tuners: 

Dragunity Darkspear is a L3 Tuner with 1000/1000 Statline. He can once per turn tribute a Dragon Monster to special a L4 or lower Winged Beast from the GY. This effect is kinda useful to recycle all the riders we just talked about minus the L5 Dragunity Primus Pilus and since that's a soft once per turn there's even some loop potential too. With Dragunity Glow , Dragunity Legion and Dragunity Militum you can get Monsters from the Spell & Trap zone back to the field and with Dragunity Legion you can even get them back from the GY. Consider that if you think about how to use Dragunity Darkspear most efficiently. Lorewise this little Dragon is Dragunity Knight - Gae Dearg.

Dragunity Guisarme is a L3 Tuner with 600/1600 Statline. He has 2 HOPT's. When normal summoned you can revive a L4 or lower Dragon/Winged Beast type Monster and negate it's effects and if equipped to a Monster you can special summon him. He's overall strong since he can act as a recovery tool and combo piece at the same time. Easy L6 or 7 Synchro lines or Link-2 lines are quite possible with him. Lorewise he's Dragunity Knight - Gormfaobhar.

Dragunity Aklys is a L2 Tuner with 1000/800 Statline. When normal summoned you can special any Dragunity Monster from the Hand and equip Aklys to it. When he's send to the GY while equipped you target and destroy a card on the field. He's part of an older kind of Playstyle Dragunity used to have and may be the best one of these nowadays. The mandatory removal with no once per turn limitations is very easy to trigger in this Deck, even multiple times in one turn and can seriously stress out the opponent. Dragunity Legion once again prooves to be useful for that but also cards like Dragunity Knight - Gormfaobhar can easily trigger him. Be sure to check the ruling page at the bottom to learn more about him. Lorewise he's Dragunity Knight - Vajrayana.

Dragunity Couse is a L2 Tuner with 1000/200 Statline. He can be treated as a L4 Tuner and can special summon himself while equipped. No once per turns to be found on this card. He's simply the best Dragon to be equipped since he can always Special summon himself onto the field as often as he wants to. I won't explain the 500+ possible lines you can go into with him so just remember play him or don't play Dragunity. Lorewise he's Dragunity Knight - Luin.

Dragunity Remus is a L2 Tuner with 800/800 Statline. He can be discarded to search Dragon Ravine and can special himself from the GY if you control a Dragunity Monster but is banished if he leaves the field then. Both effects are HOPT's. He's a great Starter and Combo piece to go into all kinds of Extra Deck plays and should always lure around in the GY to be an extra summon if needed. Lorewise he's Dragunity Knight - Romulus.

Dragunity Brandistock is a L1 Tuner with 600/400 Statline. He enables 2 attacks for the monster he is equipped to not just on Monsters but in general. Use him on Dragunity Knight - Ascalon or Dragunity Knight - Areadbhair who are equipped with Dragunity Divine Lance (Who can equip Dragunity Brandistock from Deck) and you get a 4300 ATK Monster that attacks twice and most likely an empty Board if used on Dragunity Knight - Ascalon. He may look small but little Brandi is an OTK Beast! Lorewise he has no big dragon counterpart but can be seen in the background of Dragunity Primus Pilus which may indicate that he's part of Dragunity Knight - Trident with Dragunity Javelin combined. 

To finish the small Dragon lore Dragunity Phalanx which we don't play is Dragunity Knight - Gae Bulg and Dragunity Pilum which we also don't play is Dragunity Knight - Barcha. Dragunity Knight - Ascalon is the Dragunity Divine Lance in it's dragon form and Dragunity Knight - Areadbhair may be something similar but that's not confirmed. 

Finally for this section we move to the big maindeck non tuner Dragons: 

Dragunity Arma Gram is a L10 with 2900/2200 Statline. He can be summoned from Hand or GY by banishing 2 Dragon and/or Winged Beast Monsters from the GY. He can target a face up monster, negate it's effects and reduce it's ATK by 1000 for each equip card you control. When an opponents Monster is destroyed by battle it can be equipped to this card. Each effect is a HOPT. He's easily summoned, negates effects and steals Monsters which is kinda good. It doesn't even matter which Monster destroys an opponents Monster, if Dragunity Arma Gram is on the field it can be equipped to him. The equipped Monster can even be summoned to your field with Dragunity Glow be it in defense position but that's still quite useful. The negation is permanent but isn't a quick effect. Overall he's pretty strong and a recurring threat every turn on top of all that. 

Dragunity Arma Leyvaten is a L8 with 2600/1200 Statline. He can be summoned from the Hand or GY by banishing a Monster equipped with a Dragunity card. When normal or special summoned he can equip any Dragon from the GY to himself and when sent to the GY by an opponents card effect one monster equipped to Dragunity Arma Leyvaten at that time can be special summoned. I see a lot of when... you can... on this card so there's a problem with missing timing for sure but being L8 he's an easy line into your L10 bosses and he can potentially revive your bosses too should they be equipped to him. Also in true 5DS fashion there are no once per turns on this card and just like Dragunity Arma Gram he's a recurring threat from the GY and that even multiple times in one turn. 

Dragunity Arma Mystletainn is a L6 with 2100/1500 Statline. By sending a Dragunity Monster from field to GY he can be special summoned from the Hand. When he's normal or special summoned from the Hand he can equip a Dragon from the GY to himself. He's a instant L10 Synchro summon with Dragunity Couse and can even equip other Synchro bosses from the GY to him which can then be brought into play with cards like Dragunity Militum. He can also circumvent the usage of your normal summon which is great. He truly stood the test of time and is formidable to this very day.

Finally we reached the end of this section. Let's take a look at the backrow lineup next (I promise that's shorter). 

Creation of the Divine Lance

Funny enough Dragon Ravine is the only card which has not Dragunity in it's name even so it's that central to the strategy. As a soft once per turn by discarding 1 card you can either search a L4 or lower Dragunity Monster from Deck to Hand or mill any Dragon from Deck to GY. This card is a prime example for an abusable field Spell. You can easily mill cards like Dragunity Arma Gram or search Dragunity Senatus or Dragunity Legatus and then go into a Link-2 play with Dragunity Knight - Romulus and search another Dragon Ravine, activate it and search or mill again. You could then search Dragunity Remus and search the third copy of Dragon Ravine, activate it and repeat the effect a third time in one turn. Obviously you need 3 cards to discard but since all your Monsters like to be in the GY anyway that's not a big Problem. 

Dragunity Whirlwind is a quick play spell that brings out a Dragon Tuner and Winged Beast non Tuner from the Deck with their effects negated. The opponent has to control a Monster and you have to control no Monsters for that to work. If the opponent controls a Extra Deck Monster you can immediately Synchro summon with Dragunity Monsters on the field too. A great going second and comeback tool which is always useful to get a instant L6, 7 or 8 Synchro play. Dragunity Knight - Gormfaobhar may be the best target most of the time with this card. You can only activate one Dragunity Whirlwind every turn.

Dragunity Divine Lance gives a 100 ATK Bonus times the Level of the equipped Monster and makes it unaffected by Trap effects. As a HOPT you can equip a Tuner directly from the Deck to the equipped Monster. If used as a Starter you can equip Dragunity Couse easily and start going into your Combo. If used as a finisher Dragunity Brandistock is the go to card to create a OTK Beast that attacks Twice. Note that being unaffected by Trap effects also makes it unaffected from Dragunity Oubliette's 2nd ATK gain effect.

Dragunity Glow can search or recycle a L5 or higher Dragunity Monster from the Deck/GY. You can also banish this card from the GY to special a Monster in your Spell & Trap zone which is equipped to a Dragunity Monster in defense Position to your field. Both effects are HOPT's. Searching or reusing Dragunity Arma Mystletainn is often the best usage of this card since that creates easy L10 Synchro lines. The GY effect like mentioned earlier is useful with Dragunity Arma Gram but can also special any in Archetype Monsters back to the field. 

Dragunity Oubliette is a Counter Trap that needs a Dragunity Synchro on the field to be used. It negates a Spell/Trap activation and banishes that card. If a L10 Dragunity Monster is on the field you can give a 100 ATK Bonus to a Dragunity Monster after that. For every Face up banished card it's an additional 100 ATK. Only one Dragunity Oubliette can be activated every turn. With Dragunity Knight - Areadbhair combined you have a Monster, Spell and Trap Negation which all banish the activated card on top of that. The opponent will quickly end up in an inescapable corner if these 2 cards enter the field. 

Finally Dragunity Legion is a permanent Trap that can activate one of two effects every turn. Either special summon a Dragunity Monster from the Spell/Trap Zone in defense position or equip a Dragunity Monster from the GY to one of your Dragunity Monsters. The amount of versatility this card opens up is what makes this card so useful. Whenever you may need it Dragunity Knight - Romulus can search this card.  

In total the Maindeck is pure Gas and guarantees massive Synchro swarming every turn. Let's hope these Synchro Monsters are somewhat good... well let's find out!


The Dragunity Knights Descend!

It's time for some Boss Monsters. We start with the weakest and go only up from there: 

Dragunity Knight - Romulus is your Link-2 Monster with 1200 ATK which searches your whole Spell & Trap lineup on Link summon. His 2nd effect triggers if a Dragon Monster from the Extra Deck is summoned to a zone this card points to. Then you may special summon any Dragon/Winged Beast from your Hand in defense position. That Monster has it's effects negated during that turn and can't be used as Link Material. The Main reason to play Dragunity Knight - Romulus is his easily accessible search effect. He opens up many lines into stronger cards and is a centerstone of attention in the early game. 

Dragunity Knight - Luin is a L6 Tuner with 1200/1900 Statline. His effects are HOPT's. If special summoned a Dragunity Monster from the GY can be equipped to him. Even Winged Beasts can be equipped with this effect. If sent to the GY he can be equipped to a Dragunity Monster and that Monster gains 1000 ATK/DEF. Note that he's a Tuner and his effect triggers no matter how he's special summoned. There's loop potential with Dragunity Legion , Dragunity Glow and Dragunity Militum possible. Also if his 2nd effect is used on Dragunity Knight - Gormfaobhar he can banish 2 cards from the GY every turn without loosing his equip since Luin will reequip himself. Dragunity Knight - Luin is overall a very useful addition to the strategy. 

Dragunity Knight - Vajrayana is a L6 with 1900/1200 Statline which needs a Winged Beast as a non tuner. When synchro summoned she can equip a L3 or lower Dragunity Dragon to herself. Once per turn she can send 1 of her equips to the GY to double her ATK reaching 3800 ATK easily... but wait it says current ATK! If you equip Dragunity Knight - Luin and one Dragunity Divine Lance to her before using that effect she will reach 7000 ATK until the End Phase. More Dragunity Divine Lance's or Dragunity Oubliette thrown into the mix can make this number even bigger. She turns out to be the biggest Beatstick in the whole Deck with just a little setup. Not even Obelisk shall stand in your way! 

Dragunity Knight - Gae Bulg is a L6 with 2000/1100 Statline which needs a Winged Beast as a non tuner. (The only reason to mention that is since cards like Dragunity Arma Mystletainn who can't summon these cards anyway are Dragon Monsters. Really only Dragunity Knight - Barcha and Dragunity Knight - Trident are affected by the Winged Beast limitation). Once per Battle by banishing a Winged Beast during the Damage Step the ATK of this card are increased by the original ATK of that banished Monster until the End Phase. By banishing Dragunity Primus Pilus and Dragunity Legatus or Dragunity Senatus while equipped with Dragunity Brandistock he will have 6000 ATK during the 2nd attack. Add Dragunity Divine Lance and Dragunity Knight - Luin to the mix and it's already 7600 ATK. Just like Dragunity Knight - Vajrayana he can reach very menacing ATK values very quickly and thus shouldn't be underestimated. 

Dragunity Knight - Gae Dearg is a L6 with 2400/800 Statline which needs a Winged Beast as a non tuner. His effect is the search effect of Dragon Ravine but after searching a L4 or lower Monster to the Hand, A Monster (Not a Card) has to be discarded. It's a soft once per turn on a Monster and can be looped with Dragunity Legion , Dragunity Glow and Dragunity Militum like usual. Certainly a good option to generate more advantage quickly. 

Dragunity Knight - Trident is a L7 with 2400/1700 Statline which needs a Winged Beast as a non tuner. Once per turn you can send up to 3 cards you control to the GY to look at the opponents Extra Deck and send an equal amount of cards from there to the GY. This effect sounds expensive but with a card like Dragunity Knight - Barcha it's almost free. Deleting precious cards like Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder , Accesscode Talker or that nasty Expurrely Noir is just a joy to see. You don't like Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon? Just delete it. Is Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart a problem? Just get rid of it. Not a friend of Sky Striker Ace - Kagari? Bye bye Kagari. Sprig... okay okay I think that are enough examples for now. Going first you even gain knowledge over what the opponent might be playing on top of this already strong effect. Even better as a soft once per turn you can reuse this effect with cards like Dragunity Legion quite easily. You do need 1 to 3 cards to send but that won't be bothering you much, trust me. He's a unique and very strong option and a very welcome addition especially going first. 

Dragunity Knight - Gormfaobhar is a L7 Synchro with 2600/2300 Statline. On Synchro summon a Dragunity tuner can be equipped to him and as a quick effect you can send one of the equips from him to the GY to target up to 2 cards in the opponents GY and banish them. Combined with Dragunity Knight - Luin this effect can be used every turn and Dragunity Knight - Gormfaobhar turns into a 3600 ATK beast on top of that. He makes up for a great going first tool. There's a reason people still play D.D. Crow to this very day. 

Dragunity Knight - Barcha is a L8 Synchro with 2000/1200 Statline which needs a Winged Beast non tuner. On Synchro summon any amount of Dragunity Dragons can be equipped to him from the GY (Synchro Monsters included). He gains 300 ATK for each. He can reach 3500 ATK easily with his effect alone and is perfect for bigger Combo plays. Use Dragunity Couse and go into a variety of different Synchro plays from there. Gather material for the cost of Dragunity Knight - Trident and other effects or equip Dragunity Aklys to get additional removal. You can even equip cards like Dragunity Knight - Ascalon and use Dragunity Militum to special these cards after that. Truly a card which stood the test of time and forms another centerstone of attention within this Strategy. 

Dragunity Knight - Areadbhair is a L10 Synchro with 3300/3200 Statline and 3 HOPT's. He can negate a Monster effect activation by banishing a Dragunity Monster from the GY, even in Damage Step. He can banish a Monster destroyed by Battle with him, which also happens in Damage Step and if the opponent destroys him you can destroy all Spell/Traps from the opponent. An overall strong Boss which can push the opponent easily into an inescapable corner with Dragunity Oubliette combined. He's one Card you always wanna summon to the field for sure, especially going first.

Dragunity Knight - Ascalon is a L10 Synchro with 3300/3200 Statline. Without a once per turn he can banish a Dragunity monster from the GY to target and banish a Monster from the opponent. As a HOPT if he was synchro summoned and is destroyed through the opponent you can special summon any Dragunity Synchro Monster with 3000 or less ATK from the Extra Deck (Treated as Synchro summon). Combine him with Dragunity Brandistock and Dragunity Divine Lance and you get a easy 4300 ATK threat which attacks twice, is unaffected by traps and clears all Monsters by himself. A OTK Beast for sure. The 2nd effect can be chained to a Dragunity Whirlwind as Chain Link 2 to get a bigger variety of Synchro plays available with Dragunity Whirlwind. Overall he's the best Monster in terms of agressive power that you can summon. Having both Dragunity Knight - Ascalon and Dragunity Knight - Areadbhair on the field turn one always feels good to achieve. 

And with that the Boss Monster section is now finished now we can move on to the next segment.


Cold Dust in the Dragon Ravine

Like always every Deck has it's weakpoints. Dragunity has a hard time against Dimension Shifter and Macro Cosmos. They want to setup a big GY and these cards prevent that alltogether. Necrovalley is also bad since Dragunity moves a lot of cards from the GY to other places and having that forbidden is a serious problem. 

The lack of Draw Power can also proove to be a problem. Since cards like Dragon Ravine , Dragunity Senatus and Dragunity Knight - Gae Dearg force you to discard you can end up with an empty Hand rather quickly. Then again if you successfully establish the equip ressource loop that is of no concerne anymore.

Cards like Nibiru, the Primal Being are certainly not good but also not that bad either since you play so many starters in this Deck. However a pure anti swarming strategy does hurt this Deck obviously. 

In general Dragunity is very versatile and can play around it's weakpoints pretty well in almost any Situation. 


The Final Oubliette for Trishula

Dragunity is a very unique and fun Deck for sure. If you are searching for a strong and big Combo Deck, you will like this type of strategy a lot. It can easily deal with meta Decks and the pure WIND attribute plays in it's favor even better. LIGHT and DARK are Attributes everyone is prepared for but WIND is more of an underdog and that's your advantage with this Deck. 

As for Master Duel you can easily aim for Master League with this Strategy. My advice is to go first if possible and use Dragunity Knight - Areadbhair and Dragunity Oubliette to set up negation and top it of with a Dragunity Knight - Trident who can get rid of key cards in the opponents Extra Deck Strategy, and reveal what he's playing. If you are able to also have a Dragunity Whirlwind and Dragunity Knight - Gormfaobhar ready and the perfect going first Board is established. This OTK heavy strategy shines best going second but in Master Duel many strange FTK's and mass negation Decks are the usual problems which make going first much better in 90% of cases (especially in higher leagues). 

A Deck full of Combos and Versatility is waiting for you to be explored. Dragunity is at your disposal.  


Final Rating: 

★★★★★★★ OTK Potential

★★★★☆☆☆ Defensive Tools

★★★★★★☆ Control Options

★★★★★★★ Removal Options

★★★★★★★ Recovery/Recycling

★★★★★☆☆ Card Advantage

Overall Rating: ★★★★★★☆  36/42★



Special instructions before entering the Ravine 

Just like every Duel Terminal 1 Archetype there are quite a few rules you should know about before getting started: 

About equipping: A Dragunity Monster that is equipped to something is treated as a Spell. Still cards like Dragunity Militum can bring it onto the field as a Monster. 

Dragunity Arma Gram: 1. His negation is Permanent. 2. He can target your cards too with that effect. 

Dragunity Arma Leyvaten: 1. He can miss timing. 2. If the equipped Monster is owned by the opponent you can still special summon it if he leaves the field and the timing is correct. 

Dragunity Primus Pilus: 1. He can miss timing. 2. Dragunity Aklys cannot trigger his effect because the word "then" in his card text makes him miss timing. 3. Unlike Dragunity Dux and Dragunity Legionnaire a Monster equipped with his effect stays equipped even if Skill Drain is activated. 

Dragunity Darkspear: He can tribute face down Monsters as cost for his effect. 

Dragunity Aklys: 1. His destruction effect is mandatory. 2. If the monster he's equipped to leaves the field he won't trigger his effect since he wasn't equipped to the Monster anymore. 3. His first effect has a "then" in it's text which makes When... you can... effects miss timing. 

Dragunity Brandistock: His effect is being treated as a Spell effect and is Continuous. 

Dragunity Whirlwind: If a card like Dragunity Knight - Ascalon is destroyed and his effect is about to trigger and your Board is empty, activate this card as chain link 1 and Ascalon as chain link 2. Like that you can summon bigger Synchro Monsters with the additional effect of Dragunity Whirlwind.

Dragunity Legion: This cards effects are unaffected by Dragunity Divine Lance.

Dragunity Knight - Barcha: If targeted cards leave the GY the remaining cards are still equipped to him.

Dragunity Knight - Vajrayana: 1. She can send equip cards from the opponent equipped to her to the GY to activate her effect. 2. When doubling her ATK her current ATK is checked before doubling that number. 3x Dragunity Divine Lance and Dragunity Knight - Luin equal 9400 ATK after using her effect. With Dragunity Oubliette thrown into the mix that number goes even higher. <!--/data/user/0/com.samsung.android.app.notes/files/clipdata/clipdata_bodytext_231002_122424_448.sdocx-->

deck_description:
Note: This is the most meta Dream Mirror deck specifically, not overall.

This is a WIP Dream Mirror deck and I am open to suggestions. The Prosperities can be swapped for Extrav hence the extra deck looking.....well how it does. Oh and yeah most of this deck's staples are ones that I just kinda had lying around so replace em as you see fit.

Just remeber to use Dream Traitor before popping Rite of Aramesir if you draw em both. Phantasms also acts as extra copies of Dream Traitor. If you already have a Dream Traitor in hand then Morpheus is a good one to add to hand since for main combo you could end with Tormentor and Sprite using Dream Traitor and Discple for Dream mirror of chaos. Then use Dream Mirror of Terror and on oppenents turn you can use Sprite effect to get out Mara special summoning Morpheus popping a card. If you also had Hypnagogia you could even special te Erlking after using Tormentor negate to get an extra pop.

I would generally recommend placing Dream Mirror of Terror in your field zone and giving your opponent Joy with Hypnagogia

deck_excerpt: This deck is toadally awesome (hehe get it)
deck_description:
You see, when I was first making my original Normal Monster deck, I had a thought: "Hey, this deck revolves around level 2 monsters. What if I added in spright?" I dismissed this possibility because the deck revolved around link-climbing, and spright locked you into level 2s. Later on, I had another thought: "What about Toadally Awesome? Would it work in the deck?" I gave the idea some more thought, and I realized I just had to put all three ideas together. So, I'll walk you through this deck.

Going First

This decks goal is to get out as many Toadally Awesomes as possible. In order to do this, you need to get out as many normal monsters as you can. To this end, I have included Enchanting Fitting Room and Tri-Wight. These cards allow you to swarm the field with ridiculous numbers. Ontop of that, you can also use Spright Double Cross in order to recycle your Toadally Awesomes for even more negating.

You also have your spright cards, most notably Spright Sprind. This lets you get monsters in the graveyard, which might be useful if you don't have enough to activate Tri-Wight. If you didn't draw any of your swarming cards, Gigantic Spright lets you get your normal monsters onto the field straight from the deck.

Enchanting Fitting Room is a good card, but pretty luck dependent and it restricts the deck build. You want to have as many normal monsters as possible to maximize its effect, but having too many normal monsters in hand is really bad. Luckily this deck can't really worry about it, because there are only 6 level 2 aqua normal monsters (only 3 in the tcg).

If you somehow get the best hand on earth, you might be able to end on I:P Masquerena and enough material to make Underworld Goddess of the Closed World, but it really isn't worth it. I just added it because there was so much free extra deck space I didn't know what to do with it.

Going Second

This is the most important part. When you play with someone, you will roll to see who goes first. The trick here is, you want to get the higher roll and go first. If you're playing online, you want to win the coin flip or rock-paper-scissors or whatever it is. Just make sure to go first.

After you have successfully gone first, side in all the going second stuff. You're going to need it. This deck has very little board breaking power, and because of spright restrictions its very difficult to go into Accesscode Talker or Borrelsword Dragon. So you need to preventing from bulding a board in the first place. In the worst case scenario, you have Dark Ruler No More which will buy you a turn to try something.

In conclusion this deck is like a weird off-shoot of spright frogs. It has all the same qualities, just worse. You also can't play it in the tcg, and if you want to purchase the deck, it will set you back $300.

Labrynth core with some Dogmatika support. The Dogmatika cards add a handful of special summons to throw onto the field, and a path for Alba Zoa. Alba Zoa is easier to keep safe with the Labrynth cycle happening around it.

I'm still refining this deck, and I think there's room for some Solemn cards, maybe removing some Dogmatika spells + Alba Zoa, or even the furniture and some of the traps. I'd love to hear how you might refine!

Pure Pride

I've seen various recreations of Dartz's deck, and I wanted to add my own twist to it. Let me explain how it functions.

First, we have Shining Piecephilia, a universal searcher. Its first effect lets you search for either Grand Tiki Elder (needed for Shunoros) or Shunoros itself and puts it on top of your deck. With some luck, you can draw it this turn if it survives a second attack. Its third effect allows you to search for Divine Serpent Geh as a backup if Shunoros is destroyed or any other needed monster. The fourth effect allows you to search for any card in the deck, but I recommend searching for an Equip Spell. These spells are best saved for Shunoros, as it's the ace monster. Stacking multiple equips on Shunoros can turn it into a formidable one-shot threat.

The Calculator is a great monster to have alongside Shunoros or Geh, becoming a beatstick that can protect or be protected by your boss monster when the Seal is active. Super Hippo Carnival works well with The Calculator or any monster equipped with United We Stand, serving a similar function to Dartz's Mirror Calling.

Eater Of Millions helps control the field by banishing cards, ensuring there are no problematic monsters when Shunoros is on the field. It also boosts Gren Maju Da Eiza, the deck's last beatstick. While considering a self-reviving or additional beatstick for Da Eiza, I opted for more firepower to enhance the deck's overall strength. I hope you like it !

deck_name: The Dark Magician Deck Guide (For Both Casual & Meta Players)
deck_excerpt: Explaining card choices and combos of how to play Dark Magician competitvely in 2023...
deck_description:
Dark Magician core cards are at 29-30. Its Albaz/Branded engine is at 5-7. Why? Its simple. The focus is getting DM on the field and/or getting his Fusions on the field. The goal is setting up a Dragon Knight stall board (consisting of Circle and Eternal Soul) so you can utilize your resources for the next turn while exploiting your opponent's and gaining knowledge of the cards they use or play with. 

Card analysis:

1. Magician Navigation searches for the most important cards of the deck: DM, Apprentice, Dark Illusion, and DMG. The core ratios are at 2 except Dark Illusion. You can replace Dark Illusion with Mahad since they are both at 1. With the Branded build, its better to go with Mahad instead. Your best cards to help you would be Apprentice and/or DMG for ATK boost, searching, or combos with cards such as Salvation and Combination when you use Navigation, also, Navigation can negate Spell/Trap Cards even while Dragon Knight is on the field. 

2. Secrets of Dark Magic is at 3 because you can chain while Rod gets targeted by cards such Veiler or Impermanence. Circle can make it add 1+, also, Branded can discard or you can Fusion summon furthermore using Branded. 

3. Illusion of Chaos does not need Preparation but it does need Branded Fusion to get rid of a extra card which can help your draw power with cards like Soul Servant.

4. Soul Servant searches your important cards such as DM, Rod, Timaeus, Circle, Eternal, Souls, etc. Its important to have at 3. 

5. Fusion Deployment at 1 and Branded Fusion at 3 has good synergy and can cause continuous combos in 1 turn. Fusion Deployment can be used for 1 card combo by using Cartesia or can help you with Piercing the Darkness by summoning DM to draw 1 card. Branded Fusion is 1.5 card combo that can setup your Dragon Knight board quicker and setup a potential draw 2 (draw 3 if you use Mahad instead of Dark Illusion). Since Branded locks you out Extra Deck already (except for Fusion Summoning), Deployment does not make much of a difference. You can ratio Deployment at 2 and Branded at 2. But its best to leave Deployment at 1 and Branded at 3. 

6. Allure of Darkness can aid your draw power and has synergy with Lubellion to unbanish your DARK monsters that you banished after you drawn 2 cards. You can keep Albaz in your GY while you can unbanish the other through Branded Fusion. You should also have it ratio'd at 2. You can replace it with Wonder Wand since players use Ash Blossom for Rod. If they Ash Blossom you, you can draw 2 cards by sending Rod to the GY by using Wonder Wand instead. The choice is up to whatever the player feels comfortable with between Allure or Wonder Wand. 

7. Piercing the Darkness can increase DM the Dragon Knight ATK so other monsters cannot destroy it by battle and also help you draw 1 card each turn you summon DM. 

8. Magicalized Fusion can summon an extra Dragoon in the late game and can summon Quintet to field wipe your opponent. 

9. Apprentice Illusion can help you beat boss monsters in battle such as Dragoon by giving your Spellcasters a 2000 ATK Boost. You easily destroy powerful cards like Dark Dragoon in battle just by sending Apprentice to the GY. 

Also remember the MAIN goal is to setup the Dragon Knight board, then wait until your next turn to summon heavy boss monsters after your opponent uses and wastes resources. Dark Magician was ALWAYS meant to be played This way with DM the Dragon Knight, Circle, and Eternal Soul so you come back stronger during your next turn. Hint: Magicians Rod has a recycling effect for a reason so you can get access to more cards to deal with your opponent in more ways to win your way to victory. The mistake DM players make is trying shotgun Dark Dragoon for a easy win. You will NOT ever win your duels this way. You can summon Dragoon your next turn so you can OTK your opponent more properly after having knowledge on their Deck and strategies. The card ratios for each monster and Spell/Trap are perfectly good going first or second. 

"But what about having handtraps?" Then this deck would fail with them in it so it does not matter, win or lose. 90% of the time your opponent runs out of cards to use by cramming in handtraps that make lose resources and run out of good cards to play with in their hand. But adding or changing any other cards thats on here, will ruin the deck. So dont consider it. DARK MAGICIAN BEST DECK!

A very fun Deck that could set up some floodgate and bunch of negate IF your combo go through uninterrupted.

Why not 3x Enchantress and 3x Rite? Because you really want to NOT draw into them with Radiation effect. They are dead in your hand for your combo and only serve as extender/ board breaker for the deck. I also might consider up 1 more Fateful instead because it help get rid of Crystal Girl/ Ringowurm/ Destrudo in your hand

Destrudo also is a good tribute for your Ursarctic play too. Using Destrudo to target Polari/ Pola Star/ Crystal Girl to Special Dragster at the end of your Ursarctic combo.

Crystal Girl is the perfect extender for the Deck. Just make sure NOT to activate her on NORMAL SUMMON effect so that your Adventure Engine won't turn off that turn.

Ringowurm + Polari/ Pola Star/ Crystal Girl can make you Tatsunoko then with 1 Level 7 Ursarctic in hand you can make either Gymir or the Barone.

Ringowurm + Token = Level 6 Tuners. Depend on the match up, you might want to go for Malong or Coral Dragon. Then + Level 7 Ursarctic for the Polari or Pola Star. 

Don't mind to tribute Gyphon Rider or Illegal Knight for your Ursarctic play. They are your searchable fodder and are only the back up plan for the deck.

Noted: Crystal Girl and Destrudo if SS by their own effect, you CANNOT make any Ursactic Synchro monster because of their leave the field effect. So make sure not cheat in local for this.
Memento (Oct 2023)

deck_excerpt: A Deck created by ChatGPT using the prompt "Create an Unchained deck with a short description of how the deck is played in Yu-Gi-Oh!"
deck_description:
A Deck created by ChatGPT using the prompt "Create an Unchained deck with a short description of how the deck is played in Yu-Gi-Oh!"

Please bear in mind that as useful ChatGPT is, it is by far not perfect. There will be inconsistencies and problems with deck building. Most of the time it will create a deck either under 40 cards or randomly have extra deck cards in the main deck. I've done some fine tuning whilst trying to not impact too much what ChatGPT has made.

A short description made by ChatGPT about how the deck functions.


Deck Description: Unchained Chaos

The Unchained Chaos deck harnesses the destructive power of the Unchained archetype while maintaining control over the chaos unleashed. This deck is all about breaking the chains that bind your monsters and triggering their explosive effects, leading to a cascade of destruction for your opponent.

Key Cards:

Unchained Soul of Disaster: The centerpiece of the deck, this monster can be Special Summoned by destroying two other monsters you control, setting off their effects and paving the way for its own destructive force.

Escape of the Unchained: This trap card not only protects your Unchained monsters from destruction but also triggers their effects when sent to the graveyard, allowing you to maintain board presence while disrupting your opponent.

Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring / Effect Veiler: These hand traps help you control the opponent's plays and keep them in check while your Unchained monsters wreak havoc.

How to Play:

Break the Chains: Start by summoning Unchained Twins - Aruha or Unchained Twins - Rakea to the field. You can use cards like The Dark - Hex-Sealed Fusion to facilitate this.

Trigger the Effects: Use your Unchained monsters' effects to destroy themselves, triggering their effects. Unchained Soul of Disaster can then be Special Summoned, leading to further destruction.

Disrupt Your Opponent: Utilize Escape of the Unchained to protect your monsters and trigger more effects. Your opponent will find it challenging to maintain a board presence with your continuous disruptions.

Hand Traps: Keep Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Effect Veiler ready to disrupt your opponent's key plays during their turn, maintaining your control over the duel.

Extra Deck Power: Your Extra Deck includes Unchained Abomination, Unchained Soul of Anguish, and other powerful monsters. These should be summoned strategically to deal with various threats.

Spell and Trap Support: Use cards like Dark Hole, Twin Twisters, and Harpie's Feather Duster to clear your opponent's backrow and maintain field control.

Finish Strong: When the opportunity arises, bring out formidable Link monsters like Borrelsword Dragon or Accesscode Talker to finish the duel in your favor.

The Unchained Chaos deck excels at disrupting your opponent's strategy while maintaining a strong field presence. With careful play and precise timing, you can break your own chains to unleash devastating chaos upon your foes.

deck_description:

Please bear in mind that as useful ChatGPT is, it is by far not perfect. There will be inconsistencies and problems with deck building. Most of the time it will create a deck either under 40 cards or randomly have extra deck cards in the main deck. I've done some fine tuning whilst trying to not impact too much what ChatGPT has made.

A short description made by ChatGPT about how the deck functions.

Deck Strategy:

The Drytron archetype revolves around Ritual Summoning powerful monsters and swarming the field. Here's a basic strategy:

Search Drytrons: Use cards like Cyber Emergency and Drytron Nova to search your Drytron monsters. Drytron Alpha Thuban can also search Drytron monsters when Ritual Summoned.

Ritual Summoning: Ritual Summon your Drytron monsters using Drytron Fafnir as the Ritual Spell. Drytron Beta Rastaban and Gamma Eltanin are excellent choices for Ritual Summoning as they can provide disruption and field control.

Swarm the Field: Drytron Delta Altais and Zeta Aldhibah have effects that allow you to Special Summon more Drytron monsters from your hand or deck, creating a strong field presence.

Control the Game: Drytron Nova and Drytron Eclipse provide control options by negating your opponent's cards or effects. Drytron Asterism can also disrupt your opponent's strategies.

Extra Deck Options: Your Extra Deck includes various powerful monsters for different situations. Drytron Mu Beta Fafnir can search more Ritual Spells, and Drytron Meteor Shower can clear your opponent's field. Cyber Dragon Infinity and Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy offer strong protection.

Side Deck: Customize your Side Deck based on your local meta. Include hand traps and additional disruption cards to counter popular strategies.

Adapt to Opponents: Drytron is versatile and can adapt to different opponents. Use its swarming and control abilities to outplay your opponents.

Remember that the Drytron archetype has several combo routes and can be quite flexible. Experiment with different builds and strategies to find what works best for your playstyle and local meta.

Deck from the game: Yu-Gi-Oh! The Eternal Duelist Soul

Eternal Duelist Soul is a pretty cool GBA Game, it has nice events and considerable replayability. The Decks from this game are pretty iconic and, since WC2004's decks are stored in this website already, I might aswell do the same for this game. Both games have the some really random but fitting decks for each character (almost like their anime decks).

I found these Decklists online and I'm saving them here for anyone looking for them easily (while also doing it for me). I've also tried to sort the cards by strenght, while also keeping a good organization, so it's easier to check what cards in their decks we should pay more attention to.

deck_description:
A Deck created by ChatGPT using the prompt "Create a Toon deck with a short description of how the deck is played in Yu-Gi-Oh!"

Please bear in mind that as useful ChatGPT is, it is by far not perfect. There will be inconsistencies and problems with deck building. Most of the time it will create a deck either under 40 cards or randomly have extra deck cards in the main deck. I've done some fine tuning whilst trying to not impact too much what ChatGPT has made.

A short description made by ChatGPT about how the deck functions.

Deck Strategy:

The Toon deck focuses on using Toon monsters to deal direct damage while controlling the field with Toon Kingdom. Here's a basic strategy:

Toon Kingdom: Toon Kingdom is the heart of the deck. It protects your Toon monsters from being targeted or destroyed by card effects. Make sure to have it on the field as soon as possible.

Toon Monsters: Toon Dark Magician Girl, Toon Cyber Dragon, and others are your main attackers. Toon Goblin Attack Force can attack your opponent directly, but it switches to Defense Position afterward.

Search Toons: Toon Table of Contents helps you search for Toon cards, including Toon Kingdom. Toon Mermaid can be Special Summoned if Toon World (Toon Kingdom) is on the field.

Direct Attacks: Use Toon monsters' abilities to attack your opponent's Life Points directly, bypassing their monsters.

Toon Spells: Toon Page-Flip allows you to flip your opponent's monsters face-down. Toon Rollback lets you attack with your Toon monsters twice in a turn. Comic Hand can steal your opponent's monster and turn it into a Toon.

Extra Deck: The Extra Deck includes powerful Xyz monsters like Cyber Dragon Infinity and Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy to control the field and protect your Life Points.

Card Draw: Toon Masked Sorcerer and Toon Table of Contents can help you draw additional cards to maintain hand advantage.

Protection: Toon Briefcase and Toon Mask can be used to protect your Toon monsters or disrupt your opponent's plays.

The Toon archetype is known for its fun and nostalgic playstyle. Keep in mind that while Toon monsters can be powerful, they also have some vulnerabilities, so be strategic in your plays. Adjust your Side Deck based on your local meta to enhance your deck's performance.

deck_description:
A Deck created by ChatGPT using the prompt "Create a Lightsworn deck with a short description of how the deck is played in Yu-Gi-Oh!"

Please bear in mind that as useful ChatGPT is, it is by far not perfect. There will be inconsistencies and problems with deck building. Most of the time it will create a deck either under 40 cards or randomly have extra deck cards in the main deck. I've done some fine tuning whilst trying to not impact too much what ChatGPT has made.

A short description made by ChatGPT about how the deck functions.

Deck Strategy:

The Lightsworn strategy revolves around sending cards from your deck to the graveyard to trigger various effects. Here's how to play the deck:

Mill Effect: Use cards like Raiden, Hand of the Lightsworn, Lumina, Lightsworn Summoner, and Charge of the Light Brigade to mill (send cards from your deck to the graveyard) efficiently. This fuels your graveyard with Lightsworn monsters.

Judgment Dragon: Your ultimate boss monster is Judgment Dragon. It can be Special Summoned by having four or more Lightsworn monsters with different names in your graveyard. When summoned, it can nuke the field by paying 1000 Life Points.

Supporting Lightsworn: Many Lightsworn monsters have effects that activate when sent to the graveyard, such as Wulf, Lightsworn Beast, and Felis, Lightsworn Archer. These can help you maintain board presence or disrupt your opponent.

Spell Support: Solar Recharge and Monster Reincarnation help you draw and recover key cards. Twin Twisters provides backrow removal, and Foolish Burial sends a card of your choice to the graveyard.

Extra Deck: Michael, the Arch-Lightsworn, and Minerva, the Exalted Lightsworn are key Extra Deck monsters. Michael can banish problem cards, while Minerva can help you draw and mill more.

Side Deck: Customize your Side Deck based on your local meta. Include hand traps or additional control cards as needed.

The Lightsworn deck focuses on quickly filling your graveyard with Lightsworn monsters and using Judgment Dragon as your primary win condition. It's a fast-paced and fun archetype known for its explosive plays.

deck_name: Budget Fire Kings Structure Deck x3
deck_excerpt: Scorch the field with the fires of Eternity!
deck_description:
Generate advantage by destroying your own monsters! Revive a Fire King with High Avatar Kirin! Defend Fire King Island with Avatar Arvata and Avatar Hanuman! Search for any Fire King spell or trap with the Legendary Fire King Ponix! Destroy any Fire King from the hand, deck, or field with Sacred Fire King Garunix! Use High Avatar Garunix or Garunic Eternity's effects to destroy all other monsters on the field!

Some tips

If you destroy a fire attribute monster with Fire King Island to search for Sacred Fire King Garunix, then you can special summon him from the hand with his own effect.

You can dodge the opponent's targeting cards with High Avatar Kirin's quick effect. Some examples are Infinite Impermanence, Book of Moon, and Change of Heart.

Fire King Sky Burn won't activate if your opponent controls fewer cards than the number of Fire Kings you control.

Dogoron and Herald of the Abyss provide non-targeting, non-destruction.

You can special summon Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys from the deck with Onslaught of the Fire Kings.

You can destroy your own Powersink Stone with Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys, High Avatar Kirin, Diamond Dire Wolf, or Garunic Eternity.
